const BIOLOGY_OLYMPIAD_COMPANION = [
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-la1","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"In an experiment, test tubes A and B contain water with an oil layer on top. Tube A holds a plant with roots in water; tube B has no plant. After several hours, the water level falls in A but not in B. Which explanation is scientifically correct?","options":["Evaporation from the water surface causes the level to drop in A; the oil layer is ineffective","The plant absorbs water through its roots (and loses some via transpiration); oil prevents direct evaporation, so the drop is due to plant uptake","Oil reacts chemically with root exudates in A, reducing water volume","Photosynthesis in tube B consumes water, keeping its level unchanged"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"The oil layer blocks evaporation from the surface in both tubes. In A, water is taken up by roots and lost through transpiration; B is the control with no plant uptake.","teacherTip":"Oil blocks evaporation, isolating the plant's water uptake.","examTip":"A falls due to absorption by the plant; B is the control.","linksTo":"b1kb-la1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-sa19","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following is the MOST scientifically accurate explanation for why Transpiration, despite resulting in loss of water, remains a crucial process for the plant's overall well-being?","options":["Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement","It provides a cooling effect, helping the plant cool itself when it is hot outside. Additionally, it helps maintain the concentration of the sap inside the plant body."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"It provides a cooling effect, helping the plant cool itself when it is hot outside. It helps maintain the concentration of the sap inside the plant body. It creates a suction force (transpirational pull) necessary for the ascent of sap.","teacherTip":"Cooling + sap concentration + transpiration pull.","examTip":"Give at least two benefits to justify the loss.","linksTo":"b1kb-sa19","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-la2","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"A plant shoot is placed in eosin (or safranin) dye. Stem sections show red colour in vascular bundles. What is the main objective of this experiment, and which tissue is responsible?","options":["To demonstrate food translocation through phloem","To demonstrate upward conduction of water through xylem","To show osmosis across the root epidermis only","To prove that dye is absorbed by stomata for photosynthesis"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Coloured water travels with the transpiration stream through xylem vessels, staining the water-conducting pathway from base to leaf.","teacherTip":"Coloured water rises through xylem, staining the conducting path.","examTip":"Xylem conducts; eosin/red ink reveal the path.","linksTo":"b1kb-la2","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-la3","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"A potted plant is enclosed in a polythene bag (soil uncovered) and kept in sunlight for one hour. Water droplets appear on the inner surface of the bag. Which process is demonstrated?","options":["Guttation through hydathodes at leaf margins","Transpiration — loss of water vapour from aerial parts, mainly through stomata","Respiration releasing liquid water as a by-product","Root pressure forcing liquid water out of stomata"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Water vapour released from leaves (transpiration) condenses on the cooler inner surface of the polythene bag. Uncovered soil ensures droplets are not from soil evaporation alone.","teacherTip":"Uncovered soil rules out soil evaporation; sunlight opens stomata.","examTip":"Droplets prove transpiration; stomata open in light, close in dark.","linksTo":"b1kb-la3","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa25","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following is the MOST scientifically accurate explanation for why The existence of plant life is integral to the continuity and development of most ecosystems?","options":["Energy is created de novo at each trophic level","Decomposers are primary producers in a food chain","A food chain is more stable than a food web","Plants are the primary producers — every food chain starts with plants. They supply food to nearly all terrestrial organisms, including humans, and they release oxygen on which all organisms depend for respiration. Hence plant life is integral to the continuity and development of most ecosystems."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"Plants are the primary producers — every food chain starts with plants. They supply food to nearly all terrestrial organisms, including humans, and they release oxygen on which all organisms depend for respiration. Hence plant life is integral to the continuity and development of most ecosystems.","teacherTip":"Plants provide both food and oxygen.","examTip":"Mention producers, food supply and oxygen.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa25","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-sa18","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following is the MOST scientifically accurate explanation for why Transpiration is reduced if the air is humid?","options":["On a humid day the air already contains a lot of moisture. This reduces the concentration (water-vapour) gradient between the leaf's internal air spaces and the external environment, so less water vapour diffuses out. Therefore transpiration is reduced when the air is humid.","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"On a humid day the air already contains a lot of moisture. This reduces the concentration (water-vapour) gradient between the leaf's internal air spaces and the external environment, so less water vapour diffuses out. Therefore transpiration is reduced when the air is humid.","teacherTip":"Less gradient → less water loss.","examTip":"Explain using the reduced concentration gradient.","linksTo":"b1kb-sa18","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa14","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following is the MOST scientifically accurate explanation for why Gardeners prefer to grow certain plants vegetatively?","options":["The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","Ovule develops into the fruit wall (pericarp)","Cross-pollination occurs within the same flower","Reproduction by vegetative parts takes place in a shorter time. Additionally, the new plants spread very fast in a small area."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"Reproduction by vegetative parts takes place in a shorter time. The new plants spread very fast in a small area. It is a surer method of propagation. All the good characters of the mother plant are retained by the daughter plants.","teacherTip":"Faster, surer, and keeps the parent's good traits.","examTip":"Give at least two reasons, including trait retention.","linksTo":"b2x-n9","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa15","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following is the MOST scientifically accurate explanation for why Artificial pollination is useful to plant breeders?","options":["Cross-pollination occurs within the same flower","Ovule develops into the fruit wall (pericarp)","Artificial pollination lets breeders develop new varieties. They select two varieties with desired characters (e.g. one high-yielding, the other disease-resistant) and cross-breed them by artificial pollination. Many high-yielding varieties of rice, wheat, maize, etc. have been produced this way.","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"Artificial pollination lets breeders develop new varieties. They select two varieties with desired characters (e.g. one high-yielding, the other disease-resistant) and cross-breed them by artificial pollination. Many high-yielding varieties of rice, wheat, maize, etc. have been produced this way.","teacherTip":"Combine desirable traits from two parent varieties.","examTip":"Mention combining traits to make improved varieties.","linksTo":"b2x-n12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa9","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Why are the testes located outside the abdominal cavity in the scrotum in human males?","options":["To allow greater space for sperm storage only","To maintain a temperature 2–3 °C below body temperature, which is necessary for viable sperm production","To protect testes from physical injury during locomotion","Because testosterone is produced only at ambient air temperature"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Spermatogenesis requires a temperature slightly below core body temperature; the scrotum provides this cooler environment.","teacherTip":"Cooler scrotum = healthy sperm formation.","examTip":"Link the lower temperature to sperm maturation.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa9","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa24","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following is the MOST scientifically accurate explanation for why A food web is important to maintain an ecosystem?","options":["A food web shows the complex, interdependent feeding relationships between species and the flow of energy and matter, highlighting the role of each organism. It helps maintain the natural balance of habitats. Because there are many alternative pathways, a sudden change in the population of one species does not collapse the whole system at once — so the stability of the ecosystem is maintained.","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level","Decomposers are primary producers in a food chain","A food chain is more stable than a food web"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"A food web shows the complex, interdependent feeding relationships between species and the flow of energy and matter, highlighting the role of each organism. It helps maintain the natural balance of habitats. Because there are many alternative pathways, a sudden change in the population of one species does not collapse the whole system at once — so the stability of the ecosystem is maintained.","teacherTip":"Alternative pathways give the ecosystem resilience.","examTip":"Link the food web to stability and balance.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa24","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa15","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following is the MOST scientifically accurate explanation for why The pituitary gland is considered the 'master gland'?","options":["Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland","Adrenaline lowers blood glucose during stress","Pituitary gland is located in the kidney","The pituitary gland secretes several hormones that regulate the activity of other endocrine glands. Because it controls these other glands, it is called the 'master gland'."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"The pituitary gland secretes several hormones that regulate the activity of other endocrine glands. Because it controls these other glands, it is called the 'master gland'.","teacherTip":"It directs the other endocrine glands.","examTip":"Master gland = controls other glands via its hormones.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa15","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa16","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following is the MOST scientifically accurate explanation for why Epinephrine is also called the 'emergency hormone'?","options":["Epinephrine (adrenaline) is released by the adrenal glands in response to stress. It prepares the body to meet an emergency — to face the danger or flee from the situation — so it is called the 'fight or flight' or 'emergency hormone'.","Adrenaline lowers blood glucose during stress","Pituitary gland is located in the kidney","Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"Epinephrine (adrenaline) is released by the adrenal glands in response to stress. It prepares the body to meet an emergency — to face the danger or flee from the situation — so it is called the 'fight or flight' or 'emergency hormone'.","teacherTip":"Fight-or-flight = emergency response.","examTip":"Prepares the body for sudden danger.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa16","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa17","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Public hygiene is equally important as personal hygiene. Give reasons.?","options":["Public hygiene (proper disposal of human excreta and domestic wastes) is as important as personal hygiene because:; Sewage should be chemically treated before being released into water bodies to avoid water-borne diseases, with proper sewage lines to treatment plants.","Malaria is caused by a bacterium, not a protozoan","Vaccines cure a person already suffering from the disease","Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"Public hygiene (proper disposal of human excreta and domestic wastes) is as important as personal hygiene because:; Sewage should be chemically treated before being released into water bodies to avoid water-borne diseases, with proper sewage lines to treatment plants.","teacherTip":"Community cleanliness protects everyone.","examTip":"Give reasons linked to sewage, garbage and clean water.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa17","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1x-sa5","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Water enters a root hair from soil. Why is the cell wall fully permeable but the plasma membrane semi-permeable?","options":["The cell wall actively pumps minerals inward; the membrane blocks water","The cell wall allows free passage of water and solutes; the semi-permeable membrane selectively controls osmosis, enabling water uptake against the concentration gradient of solutes","Both layers are equally permeable; osmosis occurs in the vacuole only","The cell wall is semi-permeable; the membrane is fully impermeable"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Soil water enters because cell sap is hypertonic. The freely permeable wall offers no resistance; the semi-permeable membrane controls osmotic water movement.","teacherTip":"Wall = open to all; membrane = selective gatekeeper.","examTip":"Mention osmosis, semi-permeable membrane and fully permeable wall.","linksTo":"b1x-n6","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-la5","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"In a magnified root hair cell, which structure is semi-permeable and controls osmotic entry of water?","options":["Cell wall — fully permeable to all substances","Cell membrane (plasma membrane) — allows selective passage of water by osmosis","Vacuole membrane — impermeable to all ions","Middle lamella — conducts minerals by active transport"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"The cell wall is freely permeable; the plasma membrane beneath it is semi-permeable and regulates osmotic water entry into the root hair.","teacherTip":"Cell wall = freely permeable; cell membrane = semi-permeable.","examTip":"Distinguish the freely permeable wall from the semi-permeable membrane.","linksTo":"b1kb-la5","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-sa20","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between diffusion and active transport?","options":["diffusion and active transport differ only in size, not in function or location","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","ACTIVE TRANSPORT: Movement of molecules occurs from their higher concentration to their lower concentration (down the gradient); no energy is needed.; DIFFUSION: Movement of molecules occurs from their lower concentration to a higher concentration (against the gradient), at the expense of the plant's energy (ATP).","DIFFUSION: Movement of molecules occurs from their higher concentration to their lower concentration (down the gradient); no energy is needed.; ACTIVE TRANSPORT: Movement of molecules occurs from their lower concentration to a higher concentration (against the gradient), at the expense of the plant's energy (ATP)."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"DIFFUSION: Movement of molecules occurs from their higher concentration to their lower concentration (down the gradient); no energy is needed.; ACTIVE TRANSPORT: Movement of molecules occurs from their lower concentration to a higher concentration (against the gradient), at the expense of the plant's energy (ATP).","teacherTip":"Diffusion = with gradient; active transport = against gradient + ATP.","examTip":"Compare direction relative to the concentration gradient.","linksTo":"b1kb-sa20","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-sa21","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between nitrogen and potassium?","options":["NITROGEN: A major constituent of all proteins.; POTASSIUM: More abundant in growing tissues; involved in the opening and closing of stomata.","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","nitrogen and potassium differ only in size, not in function or location","POTASSIUM: A major constituent of all proteins.; NITROGEN: More abundant in growing tissues; involved in the opening and closing of stomata."],"correctOption":0,"answer":"NITROGEN: A major constituent of all proteins.; POTASSIUM: More abundant in growing tissues; involved in the opening and closing of stomata.","teacherTip":"Nitrogen → proteins; potassium → stomatal movement.","examTip":"State the specific role of each nutrient.","linksTo":"b1kb-sa21","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-la4","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"How do temperature, light intensity and wind affect transpiration?","options":["TEMPERATURE: Higher temperatures increase the rate of transpiration due to faster evaporation of water.; LIGHT INTENSITY: In sunlight transpiration is faster as stomata open to allow inward diffusion of carbon dioxide for photosynthesis; at night the stomata close and transpiration hardly occurs.","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"TEMPERATURE: Higher temperatures increase the rate of transpiration due to faster evaporation of water.; LIGHT INTENSITY: In sunlight transpiration is faster as stomata open to allow inward diffusion of carbon dioxide for photosynthesis; at night the stomata close and transpiration hardly occurs.","teacherTip":"Each factor changes how fast water vapour leaves the leaf.","examTip":"Explain the mechanism for all three factors.","linksTo":"b1kb-la4","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa16","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between self-pollination and cross-pollination?","options":["The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","SELF-POLLINATION: Transfer of pollen grains from the anthers to the stigma of the same flower, or to another flower of the same plant.; CROSS-POLLINATION: Transfer of pollen grains from the anther of one flower to the stigma of another flower on a different plant of the same species.","CROSS-POLLINATION: Transfer of pollen grains from the anthers to the stigma of the same flower, or to another flower of the same plant.; SELF-POLLINATION: Transfer of pollen grains from the anther of one flower to the stigma of another flower on a different plant of the same species.","self-pollination and cross-pollination differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"SELF-POLLINATION: Transfer of pollen grains from the anthers to the stigma of the same flower, or to another flower of the same plant.; CROSS-POLLINATION: Transfer of pollen grains from the anther of one flower to the stigma of another flower on a different plant of the same species.","teacherTip":"Self = same plant; cross = different plants of same species.","examTip":"State the key difference: same plant vs different plant.","linksTo":"b2x-n12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa17","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between pollen grain and ovule?","options":["POLLEN GRAIN: Located in the anther (part of the androecium / stamen).; OVULE: Located in the ovary (part of the gynoecium / pistil).","OVULE: Located in the anther (part of the androecium / stamen).; POLLEN GRAIN: Located in the ovary (part of the gynoecium / pistil).","pollen grain and ovule differ only in size, not in function or location","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"POLLEN GRAIN: Located in the anther (part of the androecium / stamen).; OVULE: Located in the ovary (part of the gynoecium / pistil).","teacherTip":"Pollen = male, in anther; ovule = female, in ovary.","examTip":"Give the exact whorl that contains each.","linksTo":"b2x-n11","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa19","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between Chlorella and Spirogyra?","options":["CHLORELLA: Reproduces asexually by multiple fission.; SPIROGYRA: Reproduces asexually by fragmentation.","Chlorella and Spirogyra differ only in size, not in function or location","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","SPIROGYRA: Reproduces asexually by multiple fission.; CHLORELLA: Reproduces asexually by fragmentation."],"correctOption":0,"answer":"CHLORELLA: Reproduces asexually by multiple fission.; SPIROGYRA: Reproduces asexually by fragmentation.","teacherTip":"Chlorella → multiple fission; Spirogyra → fragmentation.","examTip":"Match each alga to its asexual method.","linksTo":"b2x-n4","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa20","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between Vallisneria and Trapa?","options":["VALLISNERIA: Pollinated by water (water-pollinated).; TRAPA: Pollinated by insects (insect-pollinated).","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","Vallisneria and Trapa differ only in size, not in function or location","TRAPA: Pollinated by water (water-pollinated).; VALLISNERIA: Pollinated by insects (insect-pollinated)."],"correctOption":0,"answer":"VALLISNERIA: Pollinated by water (water-pollinated).; TRAPA: Pollinated by insects (insect-pollinated).","teacherTip":"Vallisneria = water; Trapa = insects.","examTip":"Name the pollinating agent for each aquatic plant.","linksTo":"b2x-n12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa22","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between Term A and Term B?","options":["Term A and Term B differ only in size, not in function or location","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level","PRIMARY CONSUMERS: Feed on primary producers; they are herbivores; obtain energy from producers. Example: grasshopper eating grass.; SECONDARY CONSUMERS: Feed on primary consumers; they are carnivores or omnivores; obtain energy from primary consumers. Example: frog eating a grasshopper.","SECONDARY CONSUMERS: Feed on primary producers; they are herbivores; obtain energy from producers. Example: grasshopper eating grass.; PRIMARY CONSUMERS: Feed on primary consumers; they are carnivores or omnivores; obtain energy from primary consumers. Example: frog eating a grasshopper."],"correctOption":2,"answer":"PRIMARY CONSUMERS: Feed on primary producers; they are herbivores; obtain energy from producers. Example: grasshopper eating grass.; SECONDARY CONSUMERS: Feed on primary consumers; they are carnivores or omnivores; obtain energy from primary consumers. Example: frog eating a grasshopper.","teacherTip":"Each level eats the one below it.","examTip":"Use one continuous food chain for all three examples.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa22","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa14","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between the human male and female hormone?","options":["HUMAN MALE HORMONE: A common example is testosterone.; HUMAN FEMALE HORMONE: An example is estrogen (oestrogen).","HUMAN FEMALE HORMONE: A common example is testosterone.; HUMAN MALE HORMONE: An example is estrogen (oestrogen).","the human male and female hormone differ only in size, not in function or location","Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"HUMAN MALE HORMONE: A common example is testosterone.; HUMAN FEMALE HORMONE: An example is estrogen (oestrogen).","teacherTip":"Testosterone (male) vs estrogen (female).","examTip":"Name one sex hormone for each.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa14","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa17","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between pulmonary artery and pulmonary vein?","options":["pulmonary artery and pulmonary vein differ only in size, not in function or location","PULMONARY VEIN: Carries deoxygenated blood (from the heart to the lungs).; PULMONARY ARTERY: Carries oxygenated blood (from the lungs to the heart).","PULMONARY ARTERY: Carries deoxygenated blood (from the heart to the lungs).; PULMONARY VEIN: Carries oxygenated blood (from the lungs to the heart).","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"PULMONARY ARTERY: Carries deoxygenated blood (from the heart to the lungs).; PULMONARY VEIN: Carries oxygenated blood (from the lungs to the heart).","teacherTip":"These two are the exceptions to the usual artery/vein rule.","examTip":"Pulmonary artery = deoxygenated; pulmonary vein = oxygenated.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa17","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa19","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between closed and open vascular systems?","options":["CLOSED VASCULAR SYSTEM: Blood flows inside the body through blood vessels in a closed manner.; OPEN VASCULAR SYSTEM: Blood flows through open spaces in the body without blood vessels.","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","closed and open vascular systems differ only in size, not in function or location","OPEN VASCULAR SYSTEM: Blood flows inside the body through blood vessels in a closed manner.; CLOSED VASCULAR SYSTEM: Blood flows through open spaces in the body without blood vessels."],"correctOption":0,"answer":"CLOSED VASCULAR SYSTEM: Blood flows inside the body through blood vessels in a closed manner.; OPEN VASCULAR SYSTEM: Blood flows through open spaces in the body without blood vessels.","teacherTip":"Closed = within vessels; open = into body cavities.","examTip":"Humans have a closed vascular system.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa19","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa22","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Name any four heart-related conditions common in humans and briefly explain the cause and symptoms of each.?","options":["PALPITATIONS — the heart beats too hard, too fast, or skips a beat; usually caused by stress or anxiety (sometimes certain foods).; HYPERTENSION (high blood pressure) — blood flows through the vessels with greater force than normal; it strains the heart, damages blood vessels and raises the risk of heart attack or stroke.","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception","Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"PALPITATIONS — the heart beats too hard, too fast, or skips a beat; usually caused by stress or anxiety (sometimes certain foods).; HYPERTENSION (high blood pressure) — blood flows through the vessels with greater force than normal; it strains the heart, damages blood vessels and raises the risk of heart attack or stroke.","teacherTip":"Distinguish gradual conditions (hypertension) from sudden ones (cardiac arrest).","examTip":"Give cause + symptom for each condition.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa22","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa18","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between cranial and spinal nerves?","options":["CRANIAL NERVES: There are 12 pairs of cranial nerves.; SPINAL NERVES: There are 31 pairs of spinal nerves.","Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat","cranial and spinal nerves differ only in size, not in function or location","SPINAL NERVES: There are 12 pairs of cranial nerves.; CRANIAL NERVES: There are 31 pairs of spinal nerves."],"correctOption":0,"answer":"CRANIAL NERVES: There are 12 pairs of cranial nerves.; SPINAL NERVES: There are 31 pairs of spinal nerves.","teacherTip":"12 cranial vs 31 spinal pairs.","examTip":"Remember 12 and 31 pairs.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa18","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa20","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between cerebrum and spinal cord?","options":["Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat","CEREBRUM: The outer portion contains grey matter and the inner portion contains white matter.; SPINAL CORD: The inner part contains grey matter and the outer part contains white matter.","SPINAL CORD: The outer portion contains grey matter and the inner portion contains white matter.; CEREBRUM: The inner part contains grey matter and the outer part contains white matter.","cerebrum and spinal cord differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"CEREBRUM: The outer portion contains grey matter and the inner portion contains white matter.; SPINAL CORD: The inner part contains grey matter and the outer part contains white matter.","teacherTip":"The arrangement is reversed between the two.","examTip":"Cerebrum: grey outside; spinal cord: grey inside.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa20","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8sa1","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between communicable and non-communicable diseases. Give two examples of each.?","options":["Both communicable and non-communicable diseases. Give two examples of each. perform identical functions in all contexts","communicable and non-communicable diseases. Give two examples of each. differ only in size, not in function or location","Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold","COMMUNICABLE DISEASES: • Caused by pathogens (bacteria, virus, fungi, protozoa) • CAN spread from person to person • Spread through air, water, food, contact, or vectors • Examples"],"correctOption":3,"answer":"COMMUNICABLE DISEASES: • Caused by pathogens (bacteria, virus, fungi, protozoa) • CAN spread from person to person • Spread through air, water, food, contact, or vectors • Examples","teacherTip":"Communicable = germ + spread. Non-communicable = no germ + no spread.","examTip":"Compare at least 4 features and give 2+ examples for each type.","linksTo":"b8sa1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa18","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Briefly explain: (a) Animal husbandry, (b) Sericulture, (c) Aquaculture, (d) Hatcheries, (e) Pisciculture.?","options":["(a) Animal husbandry — the branch of biology dealing with the feeding, shelter, care and breeding of domesticated animals.; (b) Sericulture — the technique of artificial rearing of silkworms for the production of silk.","Kharif crops are sown in winter and harvested in summer","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","Green Revolution refers to increased milk production"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"(a) Animal husbandry — the branch of biology dealing with the feeding, shelter, care and breeding of domesticated animals.; (b) Sericulture — the technique of artificial rearing of silkworms for the production of silk.","teacherTip":"Each term names a specific branch of food production.","examTip":"Give a one-line meaning for each term.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa18","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1x-sa6","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: What is the ascent of sap? Explain the roles of root pressure and transpiration pull.?","options":["ASCENT OF SAP: the upward movement of water and minerals from the roots, through the xylem, to the aerial parts of the plant.; ROOT PRESSURE: the continuous inflow of water into the root cells develops a pressure that pushes the cell sap up the xylem. However, root pressure alone cannot raise water to great heights.","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"ASCENT OF SAP: the upward movement of water and minerals from the roots, through the xylem, to the aerial parts of the plant.; ROOT PRESSURE: the continuous inflow of water into the root cells develops a pressure that pushes the cell sap up the xylem. However, root pressure alone cannot raise water to great heights.","teacherTip":"Root pressure pushes from below; transpiration pull tugs from above (stronger).","examTip":"Define ascent of sap and clearly state both forces.","linksTo":"b1x-n7","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":5,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1sa1","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between xylem and phloem.?","options":["XYLEM: • Transports water and minerals • Direction: upward only (roots → leaves) • Made of dead, hollow cells • Driven by transpiration pull  PHLOEM: • Transports food (sugars) • D","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","xylem and phloem. differ only in size, not in function or location","Both xylem and phloem. perform identical functions in all contexts"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"XYLEM: • Transports water and minerals • Direction: upward only (roots → leaves) • Made of dead, hollow cells • Driven by transpiration pull  PHLOEM: • Transports food (sugars) • D","teacherTip":"Make a comparison table with at least 4 points for full marks.","examTip":"Always compare at least 4 features: what they carry, direction, cell type, and process name.","linksTo":"b1sa1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-sa22","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between xylem and phloem?","options":["PHLOEM: Conducts upwards only, i.e. from the roots to the aerial parts of the plant.; XYLEM: Conducts both upwards and downwards, i.e. from the leaves to all parts of the plant including the roots.","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","XYLEM: Conducts upwards only, i.e. from the roots to the aerial parts of the plant.; PHLOEM: Conducts both upwards and downwards, i.e. from the leaves to all parts of the plant including the roots.","xylem and phloem differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"XYLEM: Conducts upwards only, i.e. from the roots to the aerial parts of the plant.; PHLOEM: Conducts both upwards and downwards, i.e. from the leaves to all parts of the plant including the roots.","teacherTip":"Xylem = one-way up; phloem = two-way.","examTip":"Direction: xylem upward, phloem bidirectional.","linksTo":"b1kb-sa22","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa18","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between sepals and petals?","options":["PETALS: Protect the flower at the bud stage.; SEPALS: Attract insects for pollination (being large, brightly coloured and scented).","sepals and petals differ only in size, not in function or location","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","SEPALS: Protect the flower at the bud stage.; PETALS: Attract insects for pollination (being large, brightly coloured and scented)."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"SEPALS: Protect the flower at the bud stage.; PETALS: Attract insects for pollination (being large, brightly coloured and scented).","teacherTip":"Sepals protect; petals attract.","examTip":"Sepal = protection, petal = attraction.","linksTo":"b2x-n10","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa6","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between egg (ovum) and sperm.?","options":["Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition","EGG (OVUM): The female gamete; stationary, has no locomotory organ; released one at a time.  SPERM: The male gamete; capable of locomotion using a special locomotory organ (the tai","Both egg (ovum) and sperm. perform identical functions in all contexts","egg (ovum) and sperm. differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"EGG (OVUM): The female gamete; stationary, has no locomotory organ; released one at a time.  SPERM: The male gamete; capable of locomotion using a special locomotory organ (the tai","teacherTip":"Egg = large, still, one; sperm = tiny, motile, many.","examTip":"Compare motility, number and gamete type.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa6","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa7","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between sexual reproduction and asexual reproduction.?","options":["SEXUAL REPRODUCTION: Male and female gametes are involved and fertilised; two parents are involved; seen in higher organisms (e.g. humans).; ASEXUAL REPRODUCTION: Gametes are not involved; a single parent divides into two or more daughter cells; seen in lower organisms (e.g. Amoeba).","ASEXUAL REPRODUCTION: Male and female gametes are involved and fertilised; two parents are involved; seen in higher organisms (e.g. humans).; SEXUAL REPRODUCTION: Gametes are not involved; a single parent divides into two or more daughter cells; seen in lower organisms (e.g. Amoeba).","sexual reproduction and asexual reproduction. differ only in size, not in function or location","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"SEXUAL REPRODUCTION: Male and female gametes are involved and fertilised; two parents are involved; seen in higher organisms (e.g. humans).; ASEXUAL REPRODUCTION: Gametes are not involved; a single parent divides into two or more daughter cells; seen in lower organisms (e.g. Amoeba).","teacherTip":"Sexual = two parents + gametes; asexual = one parent, no gametes.","examTip":"State parent number, gamete involvement and an example for each.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa7","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa8","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between budding and regeneration.?","options":["REGENERATION: Buds grow on the outside of the parent's body and detach once capable of independent existence; it is exclusively for reproduction.; BUDDING: The process of generating lost parts of the body; mainly for regrowth of lost parts, and in some cases also for reproduction (when a cut piece develops into a new organism).","budding and regeneration. differ only in size, not in function or location","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition","BUDDING: Buds grow on the outside of the parent's body and detach once capable of independent existence; it is exclusively for reproduction.; REGENERATION: The process of generating lost parts of the body; mainly for regrowth of lost parts, and in some cases also for reproduction (when a cut piece develops into a new organism)."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"BUDDING: Buds grow on the outside of the parent's body and detach once capable of independent existence; it is exclusively for reproduction.; REGENERATION: The process of generating lost parts of the body; mainly for regrowth of lost parts, and in some cases also for reproduction (when a cut piece develops into a new organism).","teacherTip":"Budding = always reproduction; regeneration = mainly repair, sometimes reproduction.","examTip":"Contrast their main purpose: reproduction vs regrowth.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa8","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa17","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between flora and fauna.?","options":["FLORA: The plants naturally occurring in a particular area; they make their own food by photosynthesis. Examples: mosses, herbs, shrubs, trees.; FAUNA: The animals naturally living in a particular area; they cannot make their own food and depend on plants. Examples: birds, fish, insects, mammals.","flora and fauna. differ only in size, not in function or location","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level","FAUNA: The plants naturally occurring in a particular area; they make their own food by photosynthesis. Examples: mosses, herbs, shrubs, trees.; FLORA: The animals naturally living in a particular area; they cannot make their own food and depend on plants. Examples: birds, fish, insects, mammals."],"correctOption":0,"answer":"FLORA: The plants naturally occurring in a particular area; they make their own food by photosynthesis. Examples: mosses, herbs, shrubs, trees.; FAUNA: The animals naturally living in a particular area; they cannot make their own food and depend on plants. Examples: birds, fish, insects, mammals.","teacherTip":"Flora = plants; fauna = animals.","examTip":"Flora makes food; fauna depends on it.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa17","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa18","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between primary and secondary consumers.?","options":["SECONDARY CONSUMERS: Obtain their food from producers (plants). Example: krill eating grass / a deer eating grass.; PRIMARY CONSUMERS: Obtain energy by eating primary consumers (herbivores). Example: a small fish eating krill / a frog eating a grasshopper.","PRIMARY CONSUMERS: Obtain their food from producers (plants). Example: krill eating grass / a deer eating grass.; SECONDARY CONSUMERS: Obtain energy by eating primary consumers (herbivores). Example: a small fish eating krill / a frog eating a grasshopper.","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level","primary and secondary consumers. differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"PRIMARY CONSUMERS: Obtain their food from producers (plants). Example: krill eating grass / a deer eating grass.; SECONDARY CONSUMERS: Obtain energy by eating primary consumers (herbivores). Example: a small fish eating krill / a frog eating a grasshopper.","teacherTip":"Primary eat plants; secondary eat herbivores.","examTip":"Give the food source of each consumer.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa18","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa19","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between parasitism and predation.?","options":["parasitism and predation. differ only in size, not in function or location","PREDATION: A relationship between two organisms of different species in which one (the parasite) obtains its food directly from the other living organism (the host). Example: tapeworm or liver fluke in humans.; PARASITISM: An interaction in which members of one species capture, kill and eat members of another species. Example: a tiger preying on a deer.","PARASITISM: A relationship between two organisms of different species in which one (the parasite) obtains its food directly from the other living organism (the host). Example: tapeworm or liver fluke in humans.; PREDATION: An interaction in which members of one species capture, kill and eat members of another species. Example: a tiger preying on a deer.","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"PARASITISM: A relationship between two organisms of different species in which one (the parasite) obtains its food directly from the other living organism (the host). Example: tapeworm or liver fluke in humans.; PREDATION: An interaction in which members of one species capture, kill and eat members of another species. Example: a tiger preying on a deer.","teacherTip":"Parasite feeds on a living host; predator kills its prey.","examTip":"Parasitism keeps host alive; predation kills the prey.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa19","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa20","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between biotic and abiotic components.?","options":["BIOTIC COMPONENTS: The living components of the environment; they depend on abiotic components in various ways. Examples: plants, animals.; ABIOTIC COMPONENTS: The non-living components of the environment; independent of biotic components. Examples: temperature, humidity.","biotic and abiotic components. differ only in size, not in function or location","ABIOTIC COMPONENTS: The living components of the environment; they depend on abiotic components in various ways. Examples: plants, animals.; BIOTIC COMPONENTS: The non-living components of the environment; independent of biotic components. Examples: temperature, humidity.","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"BIOTIC COMPONENTS: The living components of the environment; they depend on abiotic components in various ways. Examples: plants, animals.; ABIOTIC COMPONENTS: The non-living components of the environment; independent of biotic components. Examples: temperature, humidity.","teacherTip":"Biotic = living; abiotic = non-living.","examTip":"Give one example of each component.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa20","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa21","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between scavengers and detritivores.?","options":["DETRITIVORES: Feed on dead animal and plant material; they are larger animals. Examples: vulture, hyena.; SCAVENGERS: Feed on detritus (decomposing plant and animal parts and faeces); they are smaller animals. Examples: earthworms, millipedes.","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level","scavengers and detritivores. differ only in size, not in function or location","SCAVENGERS: Feed on dead animal and plant material; they are larger animals. Examples: vulture, hyena.; DETRITIVORES: Feed on detritus (decomposing plant and animal parts and faeces); they are smaller animals. Examples: earthworms, millipedes."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"SCAVENGERS: Feed on dead animal and plant material; they are larger animals. Examples: vulture, hyena.; DETRITIVORES: Feed on detritus (decomposing plant and animal parts and faeces); they are smaller animals. Examples: earthworms, millipedes.","teacherTip":"Scavengers are big; detritivores are small.","examTip":"Compare size and food source with examples.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa21","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa26","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Explain with a suitable example: (a) Pyramid of numbers, (b) Pyramid of biomass.?","options":["(a) PYRAMID OF NUMBERS: A graphic representation of the number of organisms at each trophic level. Usually the number decreases from producers to top consumers. Example: many grass plants → fewer grasshoppers → still fewer frogs → fewer snakes → one hawk.; (b) PYRAMID OF BIOMASS: A graphic representation of the total dry weight (biomass) of organisms at each trophic level, which generally decreases from producers upwards. Example: a large mass of grass supports a smaller mass of deer, which supports an even smaller mass of tigers.","Decomposers are primary producers in a food chain","A food chain is more stable than a food web","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"(a) PYRAMID OF NUMBERS: A graphic representation of the number of organisms at each trophic level. Usually the number decreases from producers to top consumers. Example: many grass plants → fewer grasshoppers → still fewer frogs → fewer snakes → one hawk.; (b) PYRAMID OF BIOMASS: A graphic representation of the total dry weight (biomass) of organisms at each trophic level, which generally decreases from producers upwards. Example: a large mass of grass supports a smaller mass of deer, which supports an even smaller mass of tigers.","teacherTip":"Numbers and biomass both usually taper upward.","examTip":"Give a clear food-chain example for each pyramid.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa26","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa10","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between exocrine and endocrine glands?","options":["EXOCRINE GLANDS: Secrete their products (sweat, enzymes, mucus, sebum, saliva, milk, etc.) into ducts.; ENDOCRINE GLANDS: Secrete their products, called hormones, directly into the bloodstream (they are ductless).","exocrine and endocrine glands differ only in size, not in function or location","ENDOCRINE GLANDS: Secrete their products (sweat, enzymes, mucus, sebum, saliva, milk, etc.) into ducts.; EXOCRINE GLANDS: Secrete their products, called hormones, directly into the bloodstream (they are ductless).","Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"EXOCRINE GLANDS: Secrete their products (sweat, enzymes, mucus, sebum, saliva, milk, etc.) into ducts.; ENDOCRINE GLANDS: Secrete their products, called hormones, directly into the bloodstream (they are ductless).","teacherTip":"Exocrine use ducts; endocrine are ductless.","examTip":"Key difference: duct vs ductless secretion.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa10","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa11","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between cretinism and myxoedema?","options":["MYXOEDEMA: Occurs in infants, resulting in physical and mental retardation.; CRETINISM: Occurs in adults, characterised by sluggishness with swelling on the face and hands.","Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland","cretinism and myxoedema differ only in size, not in function or location","CRETINISM: Occurs in infants, resulting in physical and mental retardation.; MYXOEDEMA: Occurs in adults, characterised by sluggishness with swelling on the face and hands."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"CRETINISM: Occurs in infants, resulting in physical and mental retardation.; MYXOEDEMA: Occurs in adults, characterised by sluggishness with swelling on the face and hands.","teacherTip":"Cretinism = infants; myxoedema = adults.","examTip":"Both result from thyroxine deficiency, but at different ages.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa11","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa12","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between insulin and glucagon?","options":["insulin and glucagon differ only in size, not in function or location","Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland","INSULIN: Lowers blood glucose levels by facilitating the uptake of glucose into cells and its conversion to glycogen in the liver and muscles.; GLUCAGON: Raises blood glucose levels by promoting the conversion of glycogen back to glucose in the liver and muscles.","GLUCAGON: Lowers blood glucose levels by facilitating the uptake of glucose into cells and its conversion to glycogen in the liver and muscles.; INSULIN: Raises blood glucose levels by promoting the conversion of glycogen back to glucose in the liver and muscles."],"correctOption":2,"answer":"INSULIN: Lowers blood glucose levels by facilitating the uptake of glucose into cells and its conversion to glycogen in the liver and muscles.; GLUCAGON: Raises blood glucose levels by promoting the conversion of glycogen back to glucose in the liver and muscles.","teacherTip":"Insulin lowers, glucagon raises blood sugar.","examTip":"They have opposite effects on blood glucose.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa13","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between thyroxine and adrenaline?","options":["Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland","THYROXINE: Produced by the thyroid gland.; ADRENALINE: Produced by the adrenal glands (adrenal medulla).","ADRENALINE: Produced by the thyroid gland.; THYROXINE: Produced by the adrenal glands (adrenal medulla).","thyroxine and adrenaline differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"THYROXINE: Produced by the thyroid gland.; ADRENALINE: Produced by the adrenal glands (adrenal medulla).","teacherTip":"Thyroxine = thyroid; adrenaline = adrenal.","examTip":"Give the source gland of each hormone.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa13","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6sa1","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"What is double circulation in humans, and why is it advantageous?","options":["Blood passes through the heart once per complete body circuit","Blood passes through the heart twice for one complete circuit — pulmonary and systemic loops — ensuring fully oxygenated blood reaches tissues at high pressure","Two hearts pump blood simultaneously in parallel circuits","Blood circulates only between lungs and heart, not to body tissues"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Double circulation separates pulmonary (lung) and systemic (body) circuits, allowing efficient oxygenation and high-pressure delivery to tissues.","teacherTip":"Right side = lung circuit. Left side = body circuit. Blood visits heart twice!","examTip":"Draw the flow as: Body → Right heart → Lungs → Left heart → Body.","linksTo":"b6sa1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa18","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between artery and vein?","options":["artery and vein differ only in size, not in function or location","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","VEIN: Carries blood from the heart to various parts of the body.; ARTERY: Carries blood from different parts of the body back to the heart.","ARTERY: Carries blood from the heart to various parts of the body.; VEIN: Carries blood from different parts of the body back to the heart."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"ARTERY: Carries blood from the heart to various parts of the body.; VEIN: Carries blood from different parts of the body back to the heart.","teacherTip":"Artery away, vein toward the heart.","examTip":"Direction: artery out, vein in.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa18","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa20","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between bicuspid and tricuspid valve?","options":["bicuspid and tricuspid valve differ only in size, not in function or location","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","BICUSPID VALVE: Present between the left auricle (atrium) and the left ventricle.; TRICUSPID VALVE: Present between the right auricle (atrium) and the right ventricle.","TRICUSPID VALVE: Present between the left auricle (atrium) and the left ventricle.; BICUSPID VALVE: Present between the right auricle (atrium) and the right ventricle."],"correctOption":2,"answer":"BICUSPID VALVE: Present between the left auricle (atrium) and the left ventricle.; TRICUSPID VALVE: Present between the right auricle (atrium) and the right ventricle.","teacherTip":"Bicuspid = left; tricuspid = right.","examTip":"Give the exact chambers each valve lies between.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa20","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa21","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between blood and lymph?","options":["Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","BLOOD: The non-cellular part is plasma (about 55–60%); the cellular part consists of red cells, white cells and platelets (about 40–45%).; LYMPH: The non-cellular part is mostly water (about 94%) with about 6% proteins, fats, carbohydrates, enzymes, antibodies, etc.; the cellular part contains only leukocytes (mostly lymphocytes) — red blood cells and platelets are absent.","LYMPH: The non-cellular part is plasma (about 55–60%); the cellular part consists of red cells, white cells and platelets (about 40–45%).; BLOOD: The non-cellular part is mostly water (about 94%) with about 6% proteins, fats, carbohydrates, enzymes, antibodies, etc.; the cellular part contains only leukocytes (mostly lymphocytes) — red blood cells and platelets are absent.","blood and lymph differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"BLOOD: The non-cellular part is plasma (about 55–60%); the cellular part consists of red cells, white cells and platelets (about 40–45%).; LYMPH: The non-cellular part is mostly water (about 94%) with about 6% proteins, fats, carbohydrates, enzymes, antibodies, etc.; the cellular part contains only leukocytes (mostly lymphocytes) — red blood cells and platelets are absent.","teacherTip":"Lymph lacks RBCs and platelets.","examTip":"Compare the cellular and non-cellular parts.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa21","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa23","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Explain: (a) universal donor, (b) universal recipient.?","options":["Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception","Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma","(a) UNIVERSAL DONOR: A person with blood group O. Group O has neither antigen A nor B, so it does not cause clumping with any antibodies and can be given to all blood groups.; (b) UNIVERSAL RECIPIENT: A person with blood group AB. Group AB has no antibodies, so it does not attack the antigens of any blood group and can receive blood from all blood groups."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"(a) UNIVERSAL DONOR: A person with blood group O. Group O has neither antigen A nor B, so it does not cause clumping with any antibodies and can be given to all blood groups.; (b) UNIVERSAL RECIPIENT: A person with blood group AB. Group AB has no antibodies, so it does not attack the antigens of any blood group and can receive blood from all blood groups.","teacherTip":"O gives to all; AB receives from all.","examTip":"Link donor/recipient to antigens and antibodies.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa23","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa15","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between stimulus and response?","options":["RESPONSE: Any change in the environment that usually results in a change in the activity of the body.; STIMULUS: The activity of the body brought about due to the stimulus.","STIMULUS: Any change in the environment that usually results in a change in the activity of the body.; RESPONSE: The activity of the body brought about due to the stimulus.","Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat","stimulus and response differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"STIMULUS: Any change in the environment that usually results in a change in the activity of the body.; RESPONSE: The activity of the body brought about due to the stimulus.","teacherTip":"Stimulus causes; response results.","examTip":"Stimulus = cause, response = effect.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa15","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa16","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between receptor and effector?","options":["receptor and effector differ only in size, not in function or location","EFFECTOR: Receives the stimulus — e.g. the nerve cells in the skin that detect a stimulus.; RECEPTOR: Carries out the response — e.g. the muscle of the hand that receives the command from the brain and acts.","RECEPTOR: Receives the stimulus — e.g. the nerve cells in the skin that detect a stimulus.; EFFECTOR: Carries out the response — e.g. the muscle of the hand that receives the command from the brain and acts.","Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"RECEPTOR: Receives the stimulus — e.g. the nerve cells in the skin that detect a stimulus.; EFFECTOR: Carries out the response — e.g. the muscle of the hand that receives the command from the brain and acts.","teacherTip":"Receptor senses; effector acts.","examTip":"Skin receptor detects; hand muscle responds.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa16","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa17","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between motor nerve and sensory nerve?","options":["motor nerve and sensory nerve differ only in size, not in function or location","Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat","SENSORY NERVE: Carries impulses from the brain and spinal cord to the muscles and glands.; MOTOR NERVE: Carries impulses from the sense organs to the spinal cord or brain.","MOTOR NERVE: Carries impulses from the brain and spinal cord to the muscles and glands.; SENSORY NERVE: Carries impulses from the sense organs to the spinal cord or brain."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"MOTOR NERVE: Carries impulses from the brain and spinal cord to the muscles and glands.; SENSORY NERVE: Carries impulses from the sense organs to the spinal cord or brain.","teacherTip":"Motor out to effectors; sensory in from organs.","examTip":"Direction of impulse distinguishes the two.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa17","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa19","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between cerebrum and medulla oblongata?","options":["MEDULLA OBLONGATA: The seat of intelligence, consciousness and will power; it controls all the voluntary activities.; CEREBRUM: Controls the activities of the internal organs (involuntary actions such as heartbeat and breathing).","Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat","CEREBRUM: The seat of intelligence, consciousness and will power; it controls all the voluntary activities.; MEDULLA OBLONGATA: Controls the activities of the internal organs (involuntary actions such as heartbeat and breathing).","cerebrum and medulla oblongata differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"CEREBRUM: The seat of intelligence, consciousness and will power; it controls all the voluntary activities.; MEDULLA OBLONGATA: Controls the activities of the internal organs (involuntary actions such as heartbeat and breathing).","teacherTip":"Cerebrum = voluntary; medulla = involuntary.","examTip":"Compare voluntary vs involuntary control.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa19","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa22","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between voluntary and involuntary action, giving examples.?","options":["INVOLUNTARY ACTION: Occurs knowingly and is controlled by the cerebrum. Examples: eating an apple, watching TV.; VOLUNTARY ACTION: Occurs unknowingly and is controlled by the medulla oblongata and spinal cord. Examples: breathing, beating of the heart.","voluntary and involuntary action, giving examples. differ only in size, not in function or location","Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat","VOLUNTARY ACTION: Occurs knowingly and is controlled by the cerebrum. Examples: eating an apple, watching TV.; INVOLUNTARY ACTION: Occurs unknowingly and is controlled by the medulla oblongata and spinal cord. Examples: breathing, beating of the heart."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"VOLUNTARY ACTION: Occurs knowingly and is controlled by the cerebrum. Examples: eating an apple, watching TV.; INVOLUNTARY ACTION: Occurs unknowingly and is controlled by the medulla oblongata and spinal cord. Examples: breathing, beating of the heart.","teacherTip":"Voluntary = under our control; involuntary = automatic.","examTip":"Give one example of each type of action.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa22","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa23","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between inborn and acquired reflexes, giving examples.?","options":["INBORN REFLEXES: Need no previous experience or learning. Examples: blinking, coughing, sneezing, vomiting.; ACQUIRED REFLEXES: Develop with experience and learning during one's lifetime. Examples: typing on a keyboard, playing a musical instrument.","inborn and acquired reflexes, giving examples. differ only in size, not in function or location","Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat","ACQUIRED REFLEXES: Need no previous experience or learning. Examples: blinking, coughing, sneezing, vomiting.; INBORN REFLEXES: Develop with experience and learning during one's lifetime. Examples: typing on a keyboard, playing a musical instrument."],"correctOption":0,"answer":"INBORN REFLEXES: Need no previous experience or learning. Examples: blinking, coughing, sneezing, vomiting.; ACQUIRED REFLEXES: Develop with experience and learning during one's lifetime. Examples: typing on a keyboard, playing a musical instrument.","teacherTip":"Inborn = present at birth; acquired = learned.","examTip":"Give examples to distinguish the two reflexes.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa23","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9sa1","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between manure and fertilizers.?","options":["MANURE: • Natural/organic material (decomposed plant and animal waste) • Provides nutrients slowly over time • Improves soil structure and water-holding capacity • Adds humus to so","manure and fertilizers. differ only in size, not in function or location","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","Both manure and fertilizers. perform identical functions in all contexts"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"MANURE: • Natural/organic material (decomposed plant and animal waste) • Provides nutrients slowly over time • Improves soil structure and water-holding capacity • Adds humus to so","teacherTip":"Manure = slow food for soil. Fertilizer = fast food for soil (convenient but not always healthy).","examTip":"Compare at least 5 features in a table format for maximum marks.","linksTo":"b9sa1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa13","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between eggers (layers) and broilers.?","options":["Both eggers (layers) and broilers. perform identical functions in all contexts","EGGERS (LAYERS): Egg-laying chickens; they need food rich in vitamins, minerals and micronutrients, and require enough space and adequate lighting for proper growth.  BROILERS: Chi","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","eggers (layers) and broilers. differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"EGGERS (LAYERS): Egg-laying chickens; they need food rich in vitamins, minerals and micronutrients, and require enough space and adequate lighting for proper growth.  BROILERS: Chi","teacherTip":"Layers give eggs; broilers give meat.","examTip":"Compare purpose and feed of each.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa13","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa14","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between food crops and cash crops.?","options":["food crops and cash crops. differ only in size, not in function or location","CASH CROPS: Cultivated for the production of food. Examples: wheat, pulses.; FOOD CROPS: Cultivated for commercial purposes (to sell for profit). Examples: cotton, rubber.","FOOD CROPS: Cultivated for the production of food. Examples: wheat, pulses.; CASH CROPS: Cultivated for commercial purposes (to sell for profit). Examples: cotton, rubber.","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"FOOD CROPS: Cultivated for the production of food. Examples: wheat, pulses.; CASH CROPS: Cultivated for commercial purposes (to sell for profit). Examples: cotton, rubber.","teacherTip":"Food crops feed us; cash crops earn money.","examTip":"Give examples of each type.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa14","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa15","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between the green revolution and the white revolution.?","options":["the green revolution and the white revolution. differ only in size, not in function or location","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","WHITE REVOLUTION: Involved high-yielding crop varieties, enhanced irrigation and the use of chemical fertilisers and pesticides to increase agricultural (food grain) productivity. Father: M. S. Swaminathan.; GREEN REVOLUTION: Focused on milk production, increasing dairy yield and improving rural livelihoods through cooperative milk unions and dairy advancements. Father: Verghese Kurien.","GREEN REVOLUTION: Involved high-yielding crop varieties, enhanced irrigation and the use of chemical fertilisers and pesticides to increase agricultural (food grain) productivity. Father: M. S. Swaminathan.; WHITE REVOLUTION: Focused on milk production, increasing dairy yield and improving rural livelihoods through cooperative milk unions and dairy advancements. Father: Verghese Kurien."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"GREEN REVOLUTION: Involved high-yielding crop varieties, enhanced irrigation and the use of chemical fertilisers and pesticides to increase agricultural (food grain) productivity. Father: M. S. Swaminathan.; WHITE REVOLUTION: Focused on milk production, increasing dairy yield and improving rural livelihoods through cooperative milk unions and dairy advancements. Father: Verghese Kurien.","teacherTip":"Green = crops; white = milk.","examTip":"Name the father of each revolution.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa15","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa16","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between milch animals and draught animals.?","options":["MILCH ANIMALS: Kept for the purpose of milk production. Examples: cow, buffalo.; DRAUGHT ANIMALS: Animals (especially males) used for ploughing and carriage (heavy work). Examples: ox, camel, horse.","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","milch animals and draught animals. differ only in size, not in function or location","DRAUGHT ANIMALS: Kept for the purpose of milk production. Examples: cow, buffalo.; MILCH ANIMALS: Animals (especially males) used for ploughing and carriage (heavy work). Examples: ox, camel, horse."],"correctOption":0,"answer":"MILCH ANIMALS: Kept for the purpose of milk production. Examples: cow, buffalo.; DRAUGHT ANIMALS: Animals (especially males) used for ploughing and carriage (heavy work). Examples: ox, camel, horse.","teacherTip":"Milch = milk; draught = work.","examTip":"Give the purpose and an example of each.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa16","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa17","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between kharif crops and rabi crops.?","options":["RABI CROPS: Sown in early summer (around May), at the beginning of the first monsoon rains; known as autumn crops. Example: rice.; KHARIF CROPS: Sown around mid-November, after the monsoon rains; they are winter crops. Example: wheat.","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","KHARIF CROPS: Sown in early summer (around May), at the beginning of the first monsoon rains; known as autumn crops. Example: rice.; RABI CROPS: Sown around mid-November, after the monsoon rains; they are winter crops. Example: wheat.","kharif crops and rabi crops. differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"KHARIF CROPS: Sown in early summer (around May), at the beginning of the first monsoon rains; known as autumn crops. Example: rice.; RABI CROPS: Sown around mid-November, after the monsoon rains; they are winter crops. Example: wheat.","teacherTip":"Kharif sown with monsoon; rabi sown in winter.","examTip":"Give sowing time and one example each.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa17","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1x-sa3","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between the essential and associated elements of phloem.?","options":["the essential and associated elements of phloem. differ only in size, not in function or location","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Both the essential and associated elements of phloem. perform identical functions in all contexts","ESSENTIAL ELEMENTS — sieve tubes and companion cells. They are directly involved in the translocation of organic substances (food). Sieve tubes carry food; companion cells control "],"correctOption":3,"answer":"ESSENTIAL ELEMENTS — sieve tubes and companion cells. They are directly involved in the translocation of organic substances (food). Sieve tubes carry food; companion cells control ","teacherTip":"Essential = sieve tubes + companion cells.","examTip":"Name the cells in each group and state why they are essential or associated.","linksTo":"b1x-n4","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1x-sa4","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"How does the transport of materials differ in Amoeba, Hydra and higher plants?","options":["AMOEBA (unicellular): food and gases are exchanged directly through the cell membrane; materials move inside by streaming of cytoplasm. No transport system is needed.; HYDRA (simple multicellular): materials pass from cell to cell by simple diffusion.","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"AMOEBA (unicellular): food and gases are exchanged directly through the cell membrane; materials move inside by streaming of cytoplasm. No transport system is needed.; HYDRA (simple multicellular): materials pass from cell to cell by simple diffusion.","teacherTip":"Bigger and more complex → needs a dedicated transport system.","examTip":"Give the mechanism for each of the three organisms.","linksTo":"b1x-n5","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2x-sa1","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between asexual and sexual reproduction in plants.?","options":["asexual and sexual reproduction in plants. differ only in size, not in function or location","Both asexual and sexual reproduction in plants. perform identical functions in all contexts","ASEXUAL REPRODUCTION: 1. Involves a single parent. 2. No seeds or gametes (no fusion). 3. Offspring are identical to the parent. 4. Examples: fission, budding, fragmentation, spore","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"ASEXUAL REPRODUCTION: 1. Involves a single parent. 2. No seeds or gametes (no fusion). 3. Offspring are identical to the parent. 4. Examples: fission, budding, fragmentation, spore","teacherTip":"Key split: gamete fusion and seeds (sexual) vs none (asexual).","examTip":"Mention single parent and no seeds for asexual.","linksTo":"b2x-n1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2x-sa6","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between a bisexual and a unisexual flower, with one example of each.?","options":["UNISEXUAL FLOWER: contains BOTH the male (stamen) and female (carpel) parts. Example: Hibiscus, lily, rose.; BISEXUAL FLOWER: contains EITHER the stamen OR the carpel (only one). Example: corn, papaya.","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","a bisexual and a unisexual flower, with one example of each. differ only in size, not in function or location","BISEXUAL FLOWER: contains BOTH the male (stamen) and female (carpel) parts. Example: Hibiscus, lily, rose.; UNISEXUAL FLOWER: contains EITHER the stamen OR the carpel (only one). Example: corn, papaya."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"BISEXUAL FLOWER: contains BOTH the male (stamen) and female (carpel) parts. Example: Hibiscus, lily, rose.; UNISEXUAL FLOWER: contains EITHER the stamen OR the carpel (only one). Example: corn, papaya.","teacherTip":"Both parts = bisexual; one part = unisexual.","examTip":"Always give an example for each type.","linksTo":"b2x-n10","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2x-sa10","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Why are seeds dispersed, and what are the four methods of seed dispersal?","options":["Cross-pollination occurs within the same flower","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","WHY: seeds are dispersed to far-off places to reduce competition for sunlight, water, minerals and space, so the same plants can grow in different places.; Wind — winged (maple), light (grass) or hairy (aak) seeds.","Ovule develops into the fruit wall (pericarp)"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"WHY: seeds are dispersed to far-off places to reduce competition for sunlight, water, minerals and space, so the same plants can grow in different places.; Wind — winged (maple), light (grass) or hairy (aak) seeds.","teacherTip":"Wind, water, animals, bursting.","examTip":"State the reason (reduce competition) plus all four methods with examples.","linksTo":"b2x-n14","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa21","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: In a section of a typical flower, name the part that: (a) attaches the flower to the shoot, (b) is the flattened part of the pedicel, (c) is the outermost whorl, (d) is the male reproductive organ, (e) is the part of the carpel which receives pollen grains.?","options":["The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","Ovule develops into the fruit wall (pericarp)","(a) attaches the flower to the shoot — PEDICEL; (b) the flattened part of the pedicel — THALAMUS (receptacle)","Cross-pollination occurs within the same flower"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"(a) attaches the flower to the shoot — PEDICEL; (b) the flattened part of the pedicel — THALAMUS (receptacle)","teacherTip":"Pedicel → thalamus → calyx (outermost) → androecium; stigma catches pollen.","examTip":"Match each description to the correct flower part.","linksTo":"b2x-n11","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa10","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Why is it important that a very large number of sperms should be present in the semen?","options":["Out of the millions of sperms released into the vagina, only a few reach the upper parts of the oviducts — many die on the way and are absorbed, and only a few reach the ovum. So a very large number of sperms is needed to increase the chances of fertilisation.","Sperm and ovum are multicellular structures","Fertilization occurs in the uterus","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"Out of the millions of sperms released into the vagina, only a few reach the upper parts of the oviducts — many die on the way and are absorbed, and only a few reach the ovum. So a very large number of sperms is needed to increase the chances of fertilisation.","teacherTip":"Most sperms never reach the egg, so numbers matter.","examTip":"Connect large sperm number to higher fertilisation chance.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa10","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa12","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Based on the experimental context described, In a section of the human female reproductive system, parts 1–4 are labelled. — select the MOST accurate answer for part (a):","options":["1 → Ovary; 2 → Fallopian tube; 3 → Uterus; 4 → Vagina.","Fertilization occurs in the uterus","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition","Sperm and ovum are multicellular structures"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"1 → Ovary; 2 → Fallopian tube; 3 → Uterus; 4 → Vagina.","teacherTip":"Egg path: ovary → fallopian tube → uterus → vagina.","examTip":"Fertilisation site = fallopian tube.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa13","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Regarding a sperm and an ovum: (a) Are they unicellular or multicellular? (b) Name the organs where these gametes are produced. (c) Name the process of fusion of these gametes. (d) Name the organ where their fusion takes place. (e) What is formed by their fusion?","options":["Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition","Sperm and ovum are multicellular structures","Fertilization occurs in the uterus","(a) A sperm and an ovum are unicellular.; (b) Sperms are produced in the testes (males) and eggs in the ovaries (females)."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"(a) A sperm and an ovum are unicellular.; (b) Sperms are produced in the testes (males) and eggs in the ovaries (females).","teacherTip":"Both gametes are single cells.","examTip":"Gametes → unicellular; fusion in fallopian tube forms a zygote.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa13","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa14","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"In the human male reproductive system, which structure stores and matures sperms before they enter the urethra?","options":["Seminal vesicle — produces fructose-rich fluid only","Epididymis — coiled tubule on top of each testis where sperms mature and are stored","Prostate gland — produces the ovum for fertilization","Scrotum — site of sperm production by meiosis"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Sperms produced in seminiferous tubules of testes pass to the epididymis where they mature and are stored before ejaculation via vas deferens and urethra.","teacherTip":"Glands add fluids; testes make sperm; urethra is the shared exit.","examTip":"Give the function of each labelled male part.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa14","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa15","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Regarding reproduction in amoeba: (a) Is it sexual or asexual? (b) Name the specific kind of reproduction. (c) How many offspring are produced from one division? (d) What kind of cell division occurs? (e) Give one more example of an organism reproducing the same way.?","options":["Sperm and ovum are multicellular structures","(a) Reproduction in amoeba is asexual.; (b) It reproduces by binary fission.","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition","Fertilization occurs in the uterus"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"(a) Reproduction in amoeba is asexual.; (b) It reproduces by binary fission.","teacherTip":"Binary fission = one parent splits into two by mitosis.","examTip":"Amoeba: asexual, binary fission, two offspring, mitosis.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa15","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa16","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Based on the experimental context described, From a diagram of the human female reproductive system, name: — select the MOST accurate answer for part (a):","options":["Ovary","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition","Fertilization occurs in the uterus","Sperm and ovum are multicellular structures"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"Ovary","teacherTip":"Cervix = neck of the uterus; vagina lies between rectum and urethra.","examTip":"Match each description to the correct female organ.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa16","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa17","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Answer the following about budding: (a) Define budding. (b) Is it asexual or sexual reproduction? (c) Mention one plant and one animal example. (d) In which animal is it commonly drawn? (e) Name the specific locomotory structures of that animal.?","options":["Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition","Fertilization occurs in the uterus","Sperm and ovum are multicellular structures","(a) Budding is a form of asexual reproduction in which a protuberance (bud) grows from the parent body and develops into an independent individual.; (b) It is an asexual mode of reproduction."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"(a) Budding is a form of asexual reproduction in which a protuberance (bud) grows from the parent body and develops into an independent individual.; (b) It is an asexual mode of reproduction.","teacherTip":"Bud grows out, then detaches as a new organism.","examTip":"Budding example: Hydra (animal) and yeast (fungus).","linksTo":"b3kb-sa17","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa17","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Describe the structure of the thyroid gland as seen in its front view and back view.?","options":["Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland","FRONT VIEW: The thyroid gland is a bilobed (butterfly-shaped) gland lying on either side of the windpipe (trachea), just below the larynx, with the two lobes joined by a central band called the isthmus.; BACK VIEW: On the posterior surface, four small parathyroid glands are embedded — two on the back of each lobe of the thyroid.","Pituitary gland is located in the kidney","Adrenaline lowers blood glucose during stress"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"FRONT VIEW: The thyroid gland is a bilobed (butterfly-shaped) gland lying on either side of the windpipe (trachea), just below the larynx, with the two lobes joined by a central band called the isthmus.; BACK VIEW: On the posterior surface, four small parathyroid glands are embedded — two on the back of each lobe of the thyroid.","teacherTip":"Front shows two lobes + isthmus; back shows the parathyroids.","examTip":"Mention the isthmus (front) and parathyroid glands (back).","linksTo":"b5kb-sa17","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa24","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"During operations or accidents, a patient may be given blood from outside. What is the technical name of this process, and what precautions must be observed?","options":["The process is called blood transfusion. Precautions:; Check the compatibility of the donor's blood group with that of the recipient.","Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception","Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"The process is called blood transfusion. Precautions:; Check the compatibility of the donor's blood group with that of the recipient.","teacherTip":"Compatibility and safety checks are essential.","examTip":"Name the process and list the precautions.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa24","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa25","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Based on the experimental context described, In a diagram of the human heart — select the MOST accurate answer for part (a):","options":["Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","1 → Left pulmonary artery; 2 → Superior vena cava; 3 → Left pulmonary vein; 4 → Right auricle; 5 → Left ventricle; 6 → Right ventricle.","Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma","Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"1 → Left pulmonary artery; 2 → Superior vena cava; 3 → Left pulmonary vein; 4 → Right auricle; 5 → Left ventricle; 6 → Right ventricle.","teacherTip":"Venae cavae bring deoxygenated blood to the right auricle.","examTip":"Aorta distributes blood; right auricle receives it from the body.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa25","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa21","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Regarding a neuron: (a) What are its two main parts? (b) Is it unicellular or multicellular? (c) Which part contains the nucleus? (d) Name two parts of the body where neurons are abundant. (e) How are neurons significant to us?","options":["(a) The two main parts are the axon and the cyton (cell body).; (b) A neuron is unicellular.","Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat","Medulla oblongata is the seat of intelligence and memory","Sensory neurons carry impulses from brain to receptors"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"(a) The two main parts are the axon and the cyton (cell body).; (b) A neuron is unicellular.","teacherTip":"Cyton holds the nucleus; axon carries impulses away.","examTip":"Neuron = single cell; cyton has the nucleus.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa21","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa18","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: What is vaccination? Mention the four ways in which vaccines are prepared, giving one disease for which each type is used.?","options":["Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold","Malaria is caused by a bacterium, not a protozoan","Vaccination is the practice of artificially introducing germs or germ substances (the vaccine) into the body to develop resistance to particular diseases, usually by injection and sometimes orally. The four methods are:; Using killed germs — e.g. TAB vaccine for typhoid.","Vaccines cure a person already suffering from the disease"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"Vaccination is the practice of artificially introducing germs or germ substances (the vaccine) into the body to develop resistance to particular diseases, usually by injection and sometimes orally. The four methods are:; Using killed germs — e.g. TAB vaccine for typhoid.","teacherTip":"Match each method to its example disease.","examTip":"Give all four methods with one disease each.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa18","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa19","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Burns can be superficial, deep or chemical. What emergency care would you suggest in each case?","options":["SUPERFICIAL BURNS: Pour cold water over the burnt area, then dry that portion and cover with a sterile dressing.; DEEP BURNS: Never use water; cover the injured part with a dressing.","Vaccines cure a person already suffering from the disease","Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold","Malaria is caused by a bacterium, not a protozoan"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"SUPERFICIAL BURNS: Pour cold water over the burnt area, then dry that portion and cover with a sterile dressing.; DEEP BURNS: Never use water; cover the injured part with a dressing.","teacherTip":"Water helps superficial/chemical burns but not deep burns.","examTip":"Give the specific care for each burn type.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa19","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa20","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Write short notes on: (a) Disease, (b) Immunisation, (c) Pathogen, (d) AIDS, (e) Vaccination, (f) Vector.?","options":["(a) Disease — a departure from normal health through structural or functional disorder of the body; the two major categories are communicable (infectious) and non-communicable (non-infectious) diseases.; (b) Immunisation — an artificial way of achieving protection from infections by introducing dead or weakened germs into the body; it makes the body resistant to a specific disease through vaccination.","Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold","Vaccines cure a person already suffering from the disease","Malaria is caused by a bacterium, not a protozoan"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"(a) Disease — a departure from normal health through structural or functional disorder of the body; the two major categories are communicable (infectious) and non-communicable (non-infectious) diseases.; (b) Immunisation — an artificial way of achieving protection from infections by introducing dead or weakened germs into the body; it makes the body resistant to a specific disease through vaccination.","teacherTip":"Keep each note to 2–3 clear sentences.","examTip":"Cover the key idea of each term concisely.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa20","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa20","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Mention the benefits of the 'Green Revolution' and the 'White Revolution' in our country.?","options":["Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","Kharif crops are sown in winter and harvested in summer","Green Revolution refers to increased milk production","GREEN REVOLUTION benefits:; Enabled production of much larger quantities of food grains to feed the growing population."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"GREEN REVOLUTION benefits:; Enabled production of much larger quantities of food grains to feed the growing population.","teacherTip":"Green = food security; white = milk supply.","examTip":"List separate benefits for each revolution.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa20","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa21","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Regarding the life cycle of a silk moth: (a) What are its four stages? (b) Give the specific names for the larva and pupa. (c) Name the process of recovering threads from the killed cocoons. (d) Name a suitable plant on which these insects develop. (e) Which kind of fibre can be made from the cocoon threads?","options":["(a) The four stages are: egg, larva, pupa, adult.; (b) The larva is called the caterpillar and the pupa is called the chrysalis.","Kharif crops are sown in winter and harvested in summer","Green Revolution refers to increased milk production","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"(a) The four stages are: egg, larva, pupa, adult.; (b) The larva is called the caterpillar and the pupa is called the chrysalis.","teacherTip":"Silkworm = larva of the silk moth; it feeds on mulberry.","examTip":"Egg → larva (caterpillar) → pupa (chrysalis) → adult.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa21","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa22","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Regarding the internal structure of yeast: (a) Which kingdom does yeast belong to? (b) Is it unicellular or multicellular? (c) What is its mode of nutrition? (d) Where does yeast grow successfully? (e) Name two vitamins found in yeast. (f) Give two points on its economic importance.?","options":["Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","(b) Unicellular.; (c) Yeast has a heterotrophic mode of nutrition.","Green Revolution refers to increased milk production","Kharif crops are sown in winter and harvested in summer"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"(b) Unicellular.; (c) Yeast has a heterotrophic mode of nutrition.","teacherTip":"Yeast is a unicellular fungus used in fermentation.","examTip":"Link yeast to breweries and bakeries.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa22","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa23","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Regarding the internal structure of a bacterium: (a) Which kingdom does it belong to? (b) Is it prokaryotic or eukaryotic? (c) Name the four kinds of bacteria by shape with their shapes. (d) Name the outermost protective covering. (e) What four conditions are required for bacterial growth? (f) Name two kinds of respiration in bacteria. (g) Name the locomotory structure of bacteria.?","options":["Kharif crops are sown in winter and harvested in summer","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","(b) Prokaryotes.; (c) Four shapes: Coccus (round), Bacillus (rod-shaped), Spirillum (spiral), Vibrio (comma-shaped).","Green Revolution refers to increased milk production"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"(b) Prokaryotes.; (c) Four shapes: Coccus (round), Bacillus (rod-shaped), Spirillum (spiral), Vibrio (comma-shaped).","teacherTip":"Bacteria are prokaryotes of kingdom Monera.","examTip":"Learn the four bacterial shapes and their names.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa23","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1sa2","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: What is transpiration? State three of its functions.?","options":["Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement","TRANSPIRATION: The loss of water vapour from aerial parts of a plant, mainly through stomata on leaves.; Creates transpiration pull that helps in upward movement of water","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"TRANSPIRATION: The loss of water vapour from aerial parts of a plant, mainly through stomata on leaves.; Creates transpiration pull that helps in upward movement of water","teacherTip":"Transpiration = plant sweating. It cools AND pulls water up.","examTip":"List at least 3 functions clearly numbered for full marks.","linksTo":"b1sa2","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1ocr-sa2","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"How does transport of materials take place in unicellular plants?","options":["Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","In unicellular plants like Chlamydomonas, transport occurs by DIFFUSION — net movement of molecules from higher to lower concentration until evenly spread.","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"In unicellular plants like Chlamydomonas, transport occurs by DIFFUSION — net movement of molecules from higher to lower concentration until evenly spread.","teacherTip":"No xylem/phloem in unicellular plants.","examTip":"Unicellular → diffusion only.","linksTo":"b1ocr-sa2","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1ocr-sa4","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"How does movement and absorption of water take place through the roots?","options":["Soil water enters root hair cells by OSMOSIS (semipermeable membrane). Water then passes from cell to cell and enters the xylem. Upward movement continues via root pressure and transpiration pull through xylem vessels.","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"Soil water enters root hair cells by OSMOSIS (semipermeable membrane). Water then passes from cell to cell and enters the xylem. Upward movement continues via root pressure and transpiration pull through xylem vessels.","teacherTip":"Absorption (osmosis) then conduction (xylem).","examTip":"Mention osmosis at root hairs + xylem conduction.","linksTo":"b1ocr-sa4","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1ocr-sa5","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between osmosis and transpiration.?","options":["TRANSPIRATION: Movement of water through a semipermeable membrane from higher to lower water concentration. Occurs at root cells during water absorption. No energy needed.; OSMOSIS: Loss of water vapour from aerial parts (mainly stomata of leaves). Creates transpiration pull for upward water movement. Also cools the plant.","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","OSMOSIS: Movement of water through a semipermeable membrane from higher to lower water concentration. Occurs at root cells during water absorption. No energy needed.; TRANSPIRATION: Loss of water vapour from aerial parts (mainly stomata of leaves). Creates transpiration pull for upward water movement. Also cools the plant.","osmosis and transpiration. differ only in size, not in function or location"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"OSMOSIS: Movement of water through a semipermeable membrane from higher to lower water concentration. Occurs at root cells during water absorption. No energy needed.; TRANSPIRATION: Loss of water vapour from aerial parts (mainly stomata of leaves). Creates transpiration pull for upward water movement. Also cools the plant.","teacherTip":"Osmosis = water IN at roots. Transpiration = water OUT at leaves.","examTip":"Compare process, location, and role.","linksTo":"b1ocr-sa5","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1ocr-sa6","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which pair of statements CORRECTLY distinguishes between micronutrients and macronutrients.?","options":["MACRONUTRIENTS: Required in LARGE quantities. Examples: nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, sulphur.  MICRONUTRIENTS (trace elements): Required in VERY SMALL amoun","micronutrients and macronutrients. differ only in size, not in function or location","Both micronutrients and macronutrients. perform identical functions in all contexts","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"MACRONUTRIENTS: Required in LARGE quantities. Examples: nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, sulphur.  MICRONUTRIENTS (trace elements): Required in VERY SMALL amoun","teacherTip":"Macro = big amount; Micro = trace.","examTip":"Give definition + two examples of each.","linksTo":"b1ocr-sa6","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1ocr-sa7","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"How does transpiration create a chain of events that increases water uptake from soil?","options":["Transpiration closes stomata, trapping water inside leaves and forcing roots to absorb more","Transpiration removes water from leaves, creating transpiration pull that draws water upward through xylem, which in turn pulls water into roots from soil by osmosis","Transpiration directly pushes water into roots by root pressure alone","Transpiration converts soil minerals into water at the root surface"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Transpiration pull creates continuous tension in the xylem column, drawing water from roots; this lowers water potential at roots, pulling in more soil water by osmosis.","teacherTip":"Chain: transpiration → pull → xylem flow → root osmosis.","examTip":"Transpiration pull links leaf loss to root uptake.","linksTo":"b1ocr-sa7","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-sa15","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Under what conditions do plants transpire (a) more quickly and (b) most slowly?","options":["Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs","(a) MORE QUICKLY: on hot, dry, windy days — sunlight, high temperature, fast wind and low humidity all increase the rate of transpiration.; (b) MOST SLOWLY: on cool, humid, still days — low temperature, still air and high humidity decrease the rate of transpiration."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"(a) MORE QUICKLY: on hot, dry, windy days — sunlight, high temperature, fast wind and low humidity all increase the rate of transpiration.; (b) MOST SLOWLY: on cool, humid, still days — low temperature, still air and high humidity decrease the rate of transpiration.","teacherTip":"Hot-dry-windy speeds up; cool-humid-still slows down.","examTip":"Link each condition to its effect on transpiration.","linksTo":"b1kb-sa15","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2sa1","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"A typical complete flower of an angiosperm consists of four whorls arranged from outer to inner. Which sequence is correct?","options":["Calyx (sepals) → Corolla (petals) → Androecium (stamens) → Gynoecium (pistil)","Corolla → Calyx → Gynoecium → Androecium","Androecium → Gynoecium → Calyx → Corolla","Gynoecium → Androecium → Corolla → Calyx"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"From outside to inside: sepals (calyx) protect the bud, petals (corolla) attract pollinators, stamens (androecium) are male, and pistil (gynoecium) is female.","teacherTip":"Draw from outside in: Sepals → Petals → Stamens → Pistil (center).","examTip":"Label at least 6 parts: sepal, petal, anther, filament, stigma, ovary.","linksTo":"b2x-n10","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3sa1","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"What is the role of the placenta during pregnancy?","options":["The PLACENTA is a temporary organ that connects the developing foetus to the mother's uterine wall. Its functions:; Supplies oxygen and nutrients from mother's blood to the foetus","Fertilization occurs in the uterus","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition","Sperm and ovum are multicellular structures"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"The PLACENTA is a temporary organ that connects the developing foetus to the mother's uterine wall. Its functions:; Supplies oxygen and nutrients from mother's blood to the foetus","teacherTip":"Placenta = exchange centre + protective barrier + hormone factory.","examTip":"Mention the umbilical cord as the physical connection between foetus and placenta.","linksTo":"b3sa1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4sa1","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"What is a food web? How is it different from a food chain?","options":["Energy is created de novo at each trophic level","A food chain is more stable than a food web","Decomposers are primary producers in a food chain","FOOD CHAIN: A linear sequence showing the transfer of energy from one organism to the next.; Example: Grass → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → Eagle"],"correctOption":3,"answer":"FOOD CHAIN: A linear sequence showing the transfer of energy from one organism to the next.; Example: Grass → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → Eagle","teacherTip":"A food web is like a \"food internet\" — everything is connected to everything else.","examTip":"Always give a specific food chain example when asked about food chains or webs.","linksTo":"b4sa1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa18","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Briefly write about the importance of physical hygiene during adolescence.?","options":["Adrenaline lowers blood glucose during stress","Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland","Physical hygiene is very important for health during adolescence:; Proper and safe food: take a balanced diet (proteins, carbohydrates, fats, minerals, vitamins) with milk, fruits and fresh vegetables; avoid stale and excess fast food; store perishables in a refrigerator.","Pituitary gland is located in the kidney"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"Physical hygiene is very important for health during adolescence:; Proper and safe food: take a balanced diet (proteins, carbohydrates, fats, minerals, vitamins) with milk, fruits and fresh vegetables; avoid stale and excess fast food; store perishables in a refrigerator.","teacherTip":"Cover diet, lifestyle, cleanliness and exercise.","examTip":"Give grouped points under hygiene headings.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa18","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa19","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Briefly discuss any four activities which can be practised to overcome stress.?","options":["Adrenaline lowers blood glucose during stress","Pituitary gland is located in the kidney","Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland","Four activities to overcome stress:; Yoga — combines physical poses, controlled breathing and meditation; improves flexibility, muscle strength, respiration and energy and helps reduce stress."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"Four activities to overcome stress:; Yoga — combines physical poses, controlled breathing and meditation; improves flexibility, muscle strength, respiration and energy and helps reduce stress.","teacherTip":"Yoga, exercise, sleep and reading relieve stress.","examTip":"List four distinct stress-relieving activities.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa19","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7sa1","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which sequence correctly describes a spinal reflex arc when you withdraw your hand from a hot object?","options":["Receptor → motor neuron → brain → sensory neuron → effector","Receptor → sensory neuron → interneuron in spinal cord → motor neuron → effector","Effector → sensory neuron → cerebrum → motor neuron → receptor","Receptor → sensory neuron → cerebellum → motor neuron → effector (voluntary pathway)"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"A reflex arc processes the stimulus at the spinal cord via an interneuron, producing rapid motor response before conscious perception in the brain.","teacherTip":"5 steps: Receptor → Sensory → Spinal cord → Motor → Effector. Learn the order!","examTip":"Drawing the reflex arc as a diagram scores higher than just writing text.","linksTo":"b7sa1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa19","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"the uses of bacteria in the food industry.\"?","options":["Bacteria are used in making curd, cheese, alcohol, vinegar, etc. only — the other listed roles are incorrect","Bacteria are used in agriculture to enrich the soil with nitrates.; Curing of tea is done with the help of bacteria. (roles reversed)","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","Bacteria are used in making curd, cheese, alcohol, vinegar, etc.; Curing of tea is done with the help of bacteria.; Bacteria are used in agriculture to enrich the soil with nitrates."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"• Bacteria are used in making curd, cheese, alcohol, vinegar, etc.\n• Curing of tea is done with the help of bacteria.\n• Bacteria are used in agriculture to enrich the soil with nitrates.","teacherTip":"Bacteria help make fermented foods.","examTip":"Give at least three uses of bacteria.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa19","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1x-sa1","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"three points of difference between meristematic and permanent tissues.\"?","options":["Cells divide repeatedly. only — the other listed roles are incorrect","Cells divide repeatedly.; Cells are always living and usually lack vacuoles.; Restricted to certain parts (growing tips); responsible for growth.","Found throughout the plant body; perform storage, conduction, protection, photosynthesis.; Cells may be living or dead and have a large central vacuole. (roles reversed)","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"• Cells divide repeatedly.\n• Cells are always living and usually lack vacuoles.\n• Restricted to certain parts (growing tips); responsible for growth.","teacherTip":"Compare division, living/dead, vacuole, location, function.","examTip":"Give the comparison in clear pairs for full marks.","linksTo":"b1x-n2","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1x-sa7","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"three uses of transpiration to a plant.\"?","options":["COOLING: evaporation of water cools the plant and helps it survive hot weather. only — the other listed roles are incorrect","MAINTAINS CELL-SAP CONCENTRATION: removing excess water keeps the cell sap of the root hairs concentrated, so that water can keep entering by osmosis.; TRANSPIRATION PULL: it creates the suction that drives the upward movement of water and minerals (ascent of sap). (roles reversed)","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","COOLING: evaporation of water cools the plant and helps it survive hot weather.; TRANSPIRATION PULL: it creates the suction that drives the upward movement of water and minerals (ascent of sap).; MAINTAINS CELL-SAP CONCENTRATION: removing excess water keeps the cell sap of the root hairs concentrated, so that water can keep entering by osmosis."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"• COOLING: evaporation of water cools the plant and helps it survive hot weather.\n• TRANSPIRATION PULL: it creates the suction that drives the upward movement of water and minerals (ascent of sap).\n• MAINTAINS CELL-SAP CONCENTRATION: removing excess water keeps the cell sap of the root hairs concentrated, so that water can keep entering by osmosis.","teacherTip":"Cooling, transpiration pull, maintaining cell-sap concentration.","examTip":"Give all three uses — not just cooling.","linksTo":"b1x-n8","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1x-sa8","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"three functions of the water absorbed by a plant.\"?","options":["Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Cooling the plant through transpiration.; Production of food through photosynthesis (water is a raw material). (roles reversed)","Transport of soluble substances from one part of the plant to another.; Production of food through photosynthesis (water is a raw material).; Cooling the plant through transpiration.","Transport of soluble substances from one part of the plant to another. only — the other listed roles are incorrect"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"• Transport of soluble substances from one part of the plant to another.\n• Production of food through photosynthesis (water is a raw material).\n• Cooling the plant through transpiration.","teacherTip":"Transport, photosynthesis, cooling.","examTip":"Only ~1% of absorbed water is used in photosynthesis; list all three roles.","linksTo":"b1x-n10","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2x-sa4","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: What is tissue culture? State two of its applications.?","options":["The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","Ovule develops into the fruit wall (pericarp)","TISSUE CULTURE: a technique in which cells or tissues taken under sterile conditions are grown on a culture medium, forming a callus that develops into plantlets and finally new plants. It is also called micropropagation; the plants are genetically identical to the parent.; Produces large numbers of disease-resistant, high-yielding plants in a short time and limited space.","Cross-pollination occurs within the same flower"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"TISSUE CULTURE: a technique in which cells or tissues taken under sterile conditions are grown on a culture medium, forming a callus that develops into plantlets and finally new plants. It is also called micropropagation; the plants are genetically identical to the parent.; Produces large numbers of disease-resistant, high-yielding plants in a short time and limited space.","teacherTip":"Callus → plantlets; identical, disease-free, fast.","examTip":"Mention sterile conditions and genetically identical plants.","linksTo":"b2x-n8","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2x-sa5","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"two advantages and two disadvantages of vegetative propagation.\"?","options":["Plants grow faster and bear flowers/fruits earlier than seed-grown plants.; Offspring are exact copies of the parent, retaining all desirable characters.; All plants are identical, so a single disease can destroy the whole crop together.","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","Plants grow faster and bear flowers/fruits earlier than seed-grown plants. only — the other listed roles are incorrect","Daughter plants are crowded in a small area and compete for resources (and may carry undesirable parental traits).; All plants are identical, so a single disease can destroy the whole crop together. (roles reversed)"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"• Plants grow faster and bear flowers/fruits earlier than seed-grown plants.\n• Offspring are exact copies of the parent, retaining all desirable characters.\n• All plants are identical, so a single disease can destroy the whole crop together.","teacherTip":"Identical offspring is both the strength and the weakness.","examTip":"Give two points on each side.","linksTo":"b2x-n9","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2x-sa8","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"three characteristics of insect-pollinated flowers.\"?","options":["Their pollen grains are sticky and stick to the insect's body.; They are fragrant and produce nectar (floral rewards). (roles reversed)","They are large, colourful and showy to attract insects.; They are fragrant and produce nectar (floral rewards).; Their pollen grains are sticky and stick to the insect's body.","They are large, colourful and showy to attract insects. only — the other listed roles are incorrect","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"• They are large, colourful and showy to attract insects.\n• They are fragrant and produce nectar (floral rewards).\n• Their pollen grains are sticky and stick to the insect's body.","teacherTip":"Bright, scented, nectar, sticky pollen.","examTip":"Contrast these with wind-pollinated features.","linksTo":"b2x-n12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2x-sa9","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Describe what happens after pollination until a fruit is formed.?","options":["After pollination, a pollen tube grows from the stigma, through the style, into the ovary. The male cell travels down the pollen tube and fuses with the egg cell in the ovule — this fusion is fertilization. After fertilization, the ovary develops into the fruit and the ovules develop into the seeds.","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","Cross-pollination occurs within the same flower","Ovule develops into the fruit wall (pericarp)"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"After pollination, a pollen tube grows from the stigma, through the style, into the ovary. The male cell travels down the pollen tube and fuses with the egg cell in the ovule — this fusion is fertilization. After fertilization, the ovary develops into the fruit and the ovules develop into the seeds.","teacherTip":"Pollen tube: stigma → style → ovary → ovule.","examTip":"End with ovary → fruit and ovule → seed.","linksTo":"b2x-n13","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1sa3","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Define osmosis. How does it help in water absorption by roots?","options":["OSMOSIS: The movement of water molecules from a region of higher water concentration to a region of lower water concentration through a semi-permeable membrane.; In roots: Soil water (dilute solution) has higher water concentration than root hair cell sap (concentrated solution). So water moves from soil INTO root hair cells by osmosis through the semi-permeable cell membrane. This absorbed water then passes from cell to cell until it reaches the xylem.","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"OSMOSIS: The movement of water molecules from a region of higher water concentration to a region of lower water concentration through a semi-permeable membrane.; In roots: Soil water (dilute solution) has higher water concentration than root hair cell sap (concentrated solution). So water moves from soil INTO root hair cells by osmosis through the semi-permeable cell membrane. This absorbed water then passes from cell to cell until it reaches the xylem.","teacherTip":"Osmosis always goes from dilute to concentrated — water follows the \"thirsty\" cells.","examTip":"The three key parts of osmosis definition: water molecules, concentration gradient, semi-permeable membrane.","linksTo":"b1sa3","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b1kb-sa17","topicId":"bio-ch1","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"What are the three special features of root hairs which make them suitable for absorption of water from the soil?","options":["Osmosis requires energy in the form of ATP for water movement","Numerous root hairs provide a large surface area — more surface area means greater absorption.; Root hairs contain cell sap of higher concentration than the surrounding soil water, so water enters by osmosis.","Phloem conducts water upward from roots to leaves","Transpiration occurs primarily through root hairs"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Numerous root hairs provide a large surface area — more surface area means greater absorption.; Root hairs contain cell sap of higher concentration than the surrounding soil water, so water enters by osmosis.","teacherTip":"Large area + concentrated sap + semi-permeable membrane.","examTip":"Distinguish the permeable cell wall from the semi-permeable membrane.","linksTo":"b1kb-sa17","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa1","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which sequence is biologically CORRECT for: Arrange the following terms in a logical sequence: (a) Gestation, Birth, Fertilization, Implantation?","options":["(a) Fertilization → Implantation → Gestation → Birth → (b) Testis → Epididymis → Sperm duct → Urethra","Fertilization occurs in the uterus","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition"," Urethra →  Sperm duct  →  Epididymis  → (b) Testis  →  Birth →  Gestation  →  Implantation  → (a) Fertilization "],"correctOption":0,"answer":"(a) Fertilization → Implantation → Gestation → Birth → (b) Testis → Epididymis → Sperm duct → Urethra","teacherTip":"Follow the natural order of events / sperm path.","examTip":"Sequence both event order and structure order correctly.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa3","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: List the structures, in correct sequence, through which sperms pass from the time they are produced in the testes to the time they leave the urethra.?","options":["Testes → Sperm duct → Urethra","Fertilization occurs in the uterus","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition","Sperm and ovum are multicellular structures"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"Testes → Sperm duct → Urethra","teacherTip":"Produced in testes, carried by sperm duct, exit via urethra.","examTip":"Keep the order: testes, sperm duct, urethra.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa3","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b3kb-sa11","topicId":"bio-ch3","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"the functions of the following: (a) Ovary, (b) Testes, (c) Fallopian tubes, (d) Seminal vesicles, (e) Uterus.\"?","options":["(a) Ovary — produces eggs (ova) and secretes the reproductive hormones oestrogen and progesterone. only — the other listed roles are incorrect","(e) Uterus — the embryo grows and develops here.; (d) Seminal vesicles — produce a secretion that serves as a medium for the transport of sperms. (roles reversed)","(a) Ovary — produces eggs (ova) and secretes the reproductive hormones oestrogen and progesterone.; (b) Testes — produce and store sperms and secrete the male reproductive hormone testosterone.; (c) Fallopian tubes — transfer the egg from the ovary to the uterus (and are the site of fertilisation).","Placenta is produced by the embryo for its nutrition"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"• (a) Ovary — produces eggs (ova) and secretes the reproductive hormones oestrogen and progesterone.\n• (b) Testes — produce and store sperms and secrete the male reproductive hormone testosterone.\n• (c) Fallopian tubes — transfer the egg from the ovary to the uterus (and are the site of fertilisation).","teacherTip":"Gonads make gametes + hormones; tubes transport; uterus nurtures.","examTip":"Give the specific function of each organ.","linksTo":"b3kb-sa11","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa1","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which sequence is biologically CORRECT for: Rewrite the following in their correct sequence in a food chain: (a) Snake → Grasshopper → Grass → F?","options":[" Man →  Goat  → (e) Maize  →  Crow →  Lizard  →  Grasshopper  → (d) Grass  →  Peacock →  Snake  →  Rat  → (c) Wheat  →  Tiger →  Deer  → (b) Grass  →  Snake →  ","Decomposers are primary producers in a food chain","(a) Grass → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → (b) Grass → Deer → Tiger → (c) Wheat → Rat → Snake → Peacock → (d) Grass → Grasshopper → Lizard → Crow → (e) Maize → Go","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"(a) Grass → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → (b) Grass → Deer → Tiger → (c) Wheat → Rat → Snake → Peacock → (d) Grass → Grasshopper → Lizard → Crow → (e) Maize → Go","teacherTip":"Always start with the producer (plant).","examTip":"Begin every food chain with a green plant.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa1","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa3","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: From the words — Oikos, Food, Grasshopper, Troph, Tertiary consumer, Producers, House, Green plants, Evergreen trees, Gir forests, Ecosystem, Man, Lion — make five suitable pairs.?","options":["Energy is created de novo at each trophic level","A food chain is more stable than a food web","Decomposers are primary producers in a food chain","Green plants – Producers; Tertiary consumer – Lion"],"correctOption":3,"answer":"Green plants – Producers; Tertiary consumer – Lion","teacherTip":"Match terms to their meaning or example.","examTip":"Oikos=house, Troph=food, Lion=tertiary consumer.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa3","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa9","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"two examples of each: (a) Producers, (b) Herbivores, (c) Carnivores, (d) Predators, (e) Parasites, (f) Scavengers.\"?","options":["(a) Producers — green plants, algae only — the other listed roles are incorrect","(a) Producers — green plants, algae; (b) Herbivores — goat, grasshopper; (c) Carnivores — snakes, lizards","(f) Scavengers — vultures, crows; (e) Parasites — mosquito, tapeworm (roles reversed)","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"• (a) Producers — green plants, algae\n• (b) Herbivores — goat, grasshopper\n• (c) Carnivores — snakes, lizards","teacherTip":"Pick clear, well-known examples for each group.","examTip":"Two examples each, matching the category.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa9","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b5kb-sa8","topicId":"bio-ch5","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Write the exact locations of the following: (a) Thyroid gland, (b) Adrenal gland, (c) Pancreas, (d) Pituitary gland, (e) Adam's apple.?","options":["Insulin is secreted by the thyroid gland","(a) Thyroid gland — on either side of the windpipe, just below the larynx.; (b) Adrenal glands — on top of each kidney, like caps.","Pituitary gland is located in the kidney","Adrenaline lowers blood glucose during stress"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"(a) Thyroid gland — on either side of the windpipe, just below the larynx.; (b) Adrenal glands — on top of each kidney, like caps.","teacherTip":"Locate each gland relative to a nearby organ.","examTip":"Give a precise location for each structure.","linksTo":"b5kb-sa8","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa13","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Write one important role of each: (a) Cerebrum, (b) Cerebellum, (c) Medulla oblongata, (d) Receptors, (e) Spinal cord.?","options":["Cerebellum controls breathing and heartbeat","Medulla oblongata is the seat of intelligence and memory","Sensory neurons carry impulses from brain to receptors","(a) Cerebrum — intelligence and memory.; (b) Cerebellum — muscular coordination (and balance)."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"(a) Cerebrum — intelligence and memory.; (b) Cerebellum — muscular coordination (and balance).","teacherTip":"Each part has a clear, distinct role.","examTip":"Give one specific role for each structure.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa13","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b7kb-sa14","topicId":"bio-ch7","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which sequence correctly represents the pathway of a spinal reflex arc?","options":["Receptor → sensory neuron → interneuron in spinal cord → motor neuron → effector","Receptor → motor neuron → brain → sensory neuron → effector","Effector → sensory neuron → cerebrum → motor neuron → receptor","Receptor → sensory neuron → cerebellum → motor neuron → effector"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"A reflex arc: stimulus detected by receptor → sensory neuron → interneuron (spinal cord) → motor neuron → effector (muscle/gland) responds.","teacherTip":"Signal goes in via sensory, out via motor.","examTip":"Keep the order: receptor → CNS → effector.","linksTo":"b7kb-sa14","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa13","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"two examples of each: (a) communicable diseases, (b) non-communicable diseases, (c) viral diseases, (d) bacterial diseas\"?","options":["(a) Communicable diseases — influenza, tuberculosis; (b) Non-communicable diseases — diabetes, cardiovascular diseases; (c) Viral diseases — AIDS, chickenpox","Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold","(e) Vectors — mosquitoes, houseflies; (d) Bacterial diseases — cholera, typhoid (roles reversed)","(a) Communicable diseases — influenza, tuberculosis only — the other listed roles are incorrect"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"• (a) Communicable diseases — influenza, tuberculosis\n• (b) Non-communicable diseases — diabetes, cardiovascular diseases\n• (c) Viral diseases — AIDS, chickenpox","teacherTip":"Group each example under the correct category.","examTip":"Two clear examples for each type.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa13","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa21","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Answer these clues: (1) pathogen causing common cold and mumps; (2) may grow in unwashed hair; (3) vaccine for tuberculosis; (4) pertussis is popularly known as whooping ___; (5) a common insect that contaminates exposed food; (6) a disease that weakens the body's defence system; (7) germ/germ substance introduced to prevent infection; (8) disease in which eyes, skin and urine turn yellow; (9) organ usually affected by tuberculosis; (10) disease from an infected dog's bite affecting the CNS; (11) part of the body to cover while sneezing.?","options":["Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold","Vaccines cure a person already suffering from the disease","Malaria is caused by a bacterium, not a protozoan","1. Virus"],"correctOption":3,"answer":"1. Virus","teacherTip":"Each clue points to a single keyword.","examTip":"Match every clue to its one-word answer.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa21","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa7","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Write the two ways in which pollination may occur in plants.?","options":["Ovule develops into the fruit wall (pericarp)","Pollination may occur in two ways:; Self-pollination","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","Cross-pollination occurs within the same flower"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Pollination may occur in two ways:; Self-pollination","teacherTip":"Self = same flower/plant; cross = different plants.","examTip":"Name both types of pollination.","linksTo":"b2x-n12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa8","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"two features of flowers which favour pollination by insects.\"?","options":["The flowers are large with brightly coloured petals to attract insects.; They are scented, so insects can locate them by smell. (They also produce nectar and sticky pollen.)","The flowers are large with brightly coloured petals to attract insects. only — the other listed roles are incorrect","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","They are scented, so insects can locate them by smell. (They also produce nectar and sticky pollen.); The flowers are large with brightly coloured petals to attract insects. (roles reversed)"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"• The flowers are large with brightly coloured petals to attract insects.\n• They are scented, so insects can locate them by smell. (They also produce nectar and sticky pollen.)","teacherTip":"Bright + scented + nectar + sticky pollen attract insects.","examTip":"Give two distinct insect-attracting features.","linksTo":"b2x-n12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2kb-sa9","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"two characteristics of flowers in which pollination occurs by wind.\"?","options":["They are usually small and of dull colours. only — the other listed roles are incorrect","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","They generally have long anthers protruding out of the flower so that pollen grains are easily blown off.; They are usually small and of dull colours. (roles reversed)","They are usually small and of dull colours.; They generally have long anthers protruding out of the flower so that pollen grains are easily blown off."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"• They are usually small and of dull colours.\n• They generally have long anthers protruding out of the flower so that pollen grains are easily blown off.","teacherTip":"Wind flowers: small, dull, exposed anthers, light pollen.","examTip":"Give two features suited to wind dispersal of pollen.","linksTo":"b2x-n12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b4kb-sa23","topicId":"bio-ch4","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"any three members each of the flora and fauna of tropical rain forests.\"?","options":["FAUNA: jungle cats, leopards, monkeys.; FLORA: evergreen trees, bamboos, ferns. (roles reversed)","FLORA: evergreen trees, bamboos, ferns.; FAUNA: jungle cats, leopards, monkeys.","FLORA: evergreen trees, bamboos, ferns. only — the other listed roles are incorrect","Energy is created de novo at each trophic level"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"• FLORA: evergreen trees, bamboos, ferns.\n• FAUNA: jungle cats, leopards, monkeys.","teacherTip":"Flora = plants; fauna = animals of the rain forest.","examTip":"Give three plant and three animal examples.","linksTo":"b4kb-sa23","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa11","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"In which organ of our body does blood get oxygenated?","options":["Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception","Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma","The lungs.","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"The lungs.","teacherTip":"Gas exchange happens in the lungs.","examTip":"Blood is oxygenated in the lungs.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa11","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa12","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which side of the heart (left or right) contains oxygenated blood?","options":["Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma","The left side of the heart contains oxygenated blood.","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"The left side of the heart contains oxygenated blood.","teacherTip":"Left = oxygenated; right = deoxygenated.","examTip":"Oxygenated blood is on the left side.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa13","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Write the important role of the pericardial fluid.?","options":["Pericardial fluid protects the heart from shocks, jerks or any mechanical stress.","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception","Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"Pericardial fluid protects the heart from shocks, jerks or any mechanical stress.","teacherTip":"It cushions the heart.","examTip":"Pericardial fluid = mechanical protection.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa13","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa14","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Write the important role of the aorta.?","options":["Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception","Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma","The aorta carries oxygenated blood from the heart to all parts of the body through its branches."],"correctOption":3,"answer":"The aorta carries oxygenated blood from the heart to all parts of the body through its branches.","teacherTip":"Aorta is the largest artery.","examTip":"Aorta distributes oxygenated blood to the body.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa14","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa15","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Write the important role of the venae cavae.?","options":["The two venae cavae (superior vena cava and inferior vena cava) bring deoxygenated blood from all the different parts of the body to the right auricle (atrium) of the heart.","Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception","Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma","Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"The two venae cavae (superior vena cava and inferior vena cava) bring deoxygenated blood from all the different parts of the body to the right auricle (atrium) of the heart.","teacherTip":"Venae cavae return deoxygenated blood to the heart.","examTip":"They empty into the right atrium.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa15","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b6kb-sa16","topicId":"bio-ch6","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Give the functions of lymph.?","options":["Veins carry blood away from the heart to organs","Functions of lymph:; Drainage — it drains excess tissue fluid and metabolites and returns proteins from the tissue spaces to the blood.","Lymph contains red blood cells like blood plasma","Arteries always carry oxygenated blood without exception"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Functions of lymph:; Drainage — it drains excess tissue fluid and metabolites and returns proteins from the tissue spaces to the blood.","teacherTip":"Drainage, fat absorption and defence.","examTip":"Give all three functions of lymph.","linksTo":"b6kb-sa16","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa2","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Write the full forms of: (a) AIDS, (b) HIV, (c) WBCs, (d) BCG, (e) TAB.?","options":["(a) AIDS — Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome; (b) HIV — Human Immunodeficiency Virus","Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold","Vaccines cure a person already suffering from the disease","Malaria is caused by a bacterium, not a protozoan"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"(a) AIDS — Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome; (b) HIV — Human Immunodeficiency Virus","teacherTip":"Learn these standard medical abbreviations.","examTip":"Write the complete expanded form for each.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa2","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa14","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: What is a non-communicable disease? Answer in brief.?","options":["Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold","Non-communicable diseases are those not caused by any germ, so they cannot spread from an infected person to a healthy person (they are non-transmissible). They may be caused by improper functioning of body organs. Examples: diabetes, heart attack.","Malaria is caused by a bacterium, not a protozoan","Vaccines cure a person already suffering from the disease"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Non-communicable diseases are those not caused by any germ, so they cannot spread from an infected person to a healthy person (they are non-transmissible). They may be caused by improper functioning of body organs. Examples: diabetes, heart attack.","teacherTip":"No germ, no spread.","examTip":"Stress that these diseases do not spread.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa14","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa15","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"What are communicable diseases?","options":["Vaccines cure a person already suffering from the disease","Antibiotics are effective against viral infections like common cold","Communicable diseases are diseases that spread from an infected person to a healthy person by the entry of microorganisms or pathogens (germs). Examples: chickenpox, malaria, typhoid.","Malaria is caused by a bacterium, not a protozoan"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"Communicable diseases are diseases that spread from an infected person to a healthy person by the entry of microorganisms or pathogens (germs). Examples: chickenpox, malaria, typhoid.","teacherTip":"Caused by germs and spread between people.","examTip":"Communicable = caused by pathogens and transmissible.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa15","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b8kb-sa16","topicId":"bio-ch8","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which set of measures is MOST effective for controlling disease spread by mosquitoes and houseflies?","options":["Antibiotic treatment of all exposed individuals only","Eliminating stagnant water (mosquito breeding), covering garbage bins, proper sewage disposal, and using mosquito nets/repellents","Vaccination against all bacterial infections only","Increasing indoor humidity to kill flying insects"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Mosquitoes breed in stagnant water; houseflies breed in uncovered garbage and sewage. Source reduction plus barriers (nets, repellents) breaks the transmission cycle.","teacherTip":"Remove breeding grounds and use repellents.","examTip":"Prevent stagnant water and cover garbage.","linksTo":"b8kb-sa16","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa10","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Name any one variety of edible mushroom.?","options":["The white button mushroom (Agaricus bisporus) is an edible mushroom.","Sericulture is rearing of honeybees for honey production","Kharif crops are sown in winter and harvested in summer","Green Revolution refers to increased milk production"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"The white button mushroom (Agaricus bisporus) is an edible mushroom.","teacherTip":"White button mushroom is the most common edible type.","examTip":"Give one edible mushroom with its name.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa10","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b9kb-sa12","topicId":"bio-ch9","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"What is organic farming and what is its primary aim?","options":["Using synthetic chemical fertilisers for maximum yield — aim: profit maximisation","Cultivation without synthetic chemicals, using compost, manure and bio-pesticides — aim: sustainable agriculture with minimal environmental harm","Growing crops only in greenhouses with artificial light","Replacing all crops with genetically modified high-yield varieties only"],"correctOption":1,"answer":"Organic farming avoids synthetic fertilisers and pesticides, relying on natural inputs to maintain soil fertility and ecological balance sustainably.","teacherTip":"Organic = no synthetic chemicals.","examTip":"Mention the eco-friendly, chemical-free aim.","linksTo":"b9kb-sa12","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2x-sa3","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which option CORRECTLY addresses: \"Name the four kinds of artificial vegetative propagation and give one example of each.\"?","options":["CUTTING — a plant from a piece of stem/root (e.g. rose, sugarcane).; GRAFTING — joining a scion to a rooted stock (e.g. mango, citrus).; LAYERING — burying a bent branch in moist soil until it roots (e.g. jasmine, strawberry).","TISSUE CULTURE (micropropagation) — growing plants from cells/tissue in sterile culture (e.g. orchids, Chrysanthemum).; LAYERING — burying a bent branch in moist soil until it roots (e.g. jasmine, strawberry). (roles reversed)","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization","CUTTING — a plant from a piece of stem/root (e.g. rose, sugarcane). only — the other listed roles are incorrect"],"correctOption":0,"answer":"• CUTTING — a plant from a piece of stem/root (e.g. rose, sugarcane).\n• GRAFTING — joining a scion to a rooted stock (e.g. mango, citrus).\n• LAYERING — burying a bent branch in moist soil until it roots (e.g. jasmine, strawberry).","teacherTip":"Cutting, grafting, layering, tissue culture.","examTip":"Give one named plant example for each method.","linksTo":"b2x-n7","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"},
{"id":"bio-ol-b2x-sa7","topicId":"bio-ch2","type":"mcq","subtopic":"Olympiad / NEET Companion MCQ","question":"Which of the following BEST answers: Name the parts of a stamen and a pistil, and state where the male and female gametes are produced.?","options":["Cross-pollination occurs within the same flower","Ovule develops into the fruit wall (pericarp)","STAMEN (male): anther + filament. The ANTHER contains pollen grains and produces the male gametes.; PISTIL/CARPEL (female): stigma + style + ovary. The ovary contains ovules, and the female gamete (egg) is produced inside the OVULE.","The anther develops into fruit after fertilization"],"correctOption":2,"answer":"STAMEN (male): anther + filament. The ANTHER contains pollen grains and produces the male gametes.; PISTIL/CARPEL (female): stigma + style + ovary. The ovary contains ovules, and the female gamete (egg) is produced inside the OVULE.","teacherTip":"Pollen from anther; egg from ovule.","examTip":"List every part and link gamete production to anther and ovule.","linksTo":"b2x-n11","source":"olympiad","qualityStars":4,"qualityLevel":"Olympiad"}
];
